# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sicily
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The **1693 Sicily earthquake** was a natural disaster that struck parts of southern Italy near Sicily, then a territory part of the Crown of Aragon by the Kings of Spain Calabria and Malta, on 11 January at around 21:00 local time.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] This earthquake was preceded by a damaging foreshock on 9 January.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The earthquake was followed by a number of tsunamis that devastated the coastal villages on the Ionian Sea and in the Straits of Messina.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Almost two-thirds of the entire population of Catania were killed.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The epicentre of the disaster was probably close to the coast, possibly offshore, although the exact position remains unknown.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The extent and level of destruction caused by the earthquake resulted in the extensive rebuilding of the towns and cities of southeastern Sicily, particularly the Val di Noto, in a homogeneous late Baroque style, described as "the culmination and final flowering of Baroque art in Europe".
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Sicily lies on part of the complex convergent boundary where the African plate is subducting beneath the Eurasian plate.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] This subduction zone is responsible for the formation of the stratovolcano Mount Etna and considerable seismic activity.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Most damaging earthquakes however, occur on the Siculo-Calabrian rift zone.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] This zone of extensional faulting runs for about 370 kilometres (230 mi), forming three main segments through Calabria, along the east coast of Sicily and immediately offshore, and finally forming the southeastern margin of the Hyblaean Plateau.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Faults in the Calabrian segment were responsible for the 1783 Calabrian earthquakes sequence.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] In the southern part of the eastern coast of Sicily, investigations have identified a series of active normal faults, dipping to the east.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Most of these lie offshore and some control basins that contain large thicknesses of Quaternary sediments.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The two largest faults, known as the western and eastern master faults, border half-grabens with fills of up to 700 metres (2,300 ft) and 800 metres (2,600 ft) respectively.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Onshore, two ages of faulting have been recognised, an earlier phase trending NW-SE and a later phase trending SSW-NNE that clearly offsets the first group, including the Avola fault and the Rosolini-Ispica fault system.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] A destructive earthquake occurred two days before the mainshock at 21:00 local time, centered in the Val di Noto.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] It had an estimated magnitude of 6.2 and a maximum perceived intensity of VIII–XI on the Mercalli intensity scale.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Intensities of VIII or higher have been estimated for Augusta, Avola Vecchia, Floridia, Melilli, Noto Antica, Catania, Francofonte, Lentini, Scicli, Sortino and Vizzini.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Augusta lies well outside the main zone of severe shaking; its extensive damage is probably due to its construction on unconsolidated sediments.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] From the shape and location of the area of maximum damage, the earthquake is thought to have been caused by movement on the Avola fault.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The earthquake lasted for four minutes, according to contemporary accounts.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The estimated magnitude of 7.4 is taken from the extent and degree of the recorded damage, with a very large area that reached X (*Extreme*) or more on the Mercalli scale.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The maximum shaking reached XI in the towns of Buscemi, Floridia, Melilli, Occhiola and Sortino.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The source of the 11 January earthquake is debated.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] An analysis of the distribution of tsunami run-ups along the coast suggests that a submarine landslide triggered by the earthquake is the most likely source, in which case the tsunami provides no constraint on the epicenter.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] A landslide origin is supported by the observation of possible landslide bodies along the Hyblean-Malta escarpment.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Historic documents in the Archivo General de Simancas mention dozens of aftershocks, some as late as August 1694, and some reportedly as strong as the initial quake of 11 January 1693.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Aftershocks continued until at least 1696, with their effects concentrated in towns along the coast, supporting an epicentre either near the coast or offshore.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The tsunami triggered by the earthquake affected most of the Ionian Sea coast of Sicily, about 230 kilometres (140 mi) in all.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The first thing that was noted at all localities affected was a withdrawal of the sea.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The strongest effects were concentrated around Augusta, where the initial withdrawal left the harbour dry, followed by a wave of at least 2.4 metres (7.9 ft) height, possibly as much as 8 metres (26 ft), that inundated part of the town.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The maximum inundation of about 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) was recorded at Mascali.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Tsunami deposits linked to the 1693 tsunami have been found both onshore and offshore.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] At Ognina, just south of Syracuse, at the head of a ria, a sequence containing several coarse clastic layers has been found, inconsistent with its lagoonal setting.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The uppermost coarse layer, which has a strongly erosive base, consists of coarse sand with up to granule size clasts.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The layer has been dated as 17th to 18th century based on pottery shards and one well-preserved clay pipe, consistent with the 1693 tsunami.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Offshore from Augusta, a sequence identified using chirp sonar data was sampled with a 6.7 metres (22 ft) gravity core in 72 metres (236 ft) of water.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Following detailed analysis of both grain size and foraminifera assemblages, eleven possible high-energy events were found based on the presence of large numbers of shallow water forams combined with a greater proportion of fine sand in the same interval.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The uppermost two events correlate well with the tsunamis from the 1908 Messina earthquake and the 1693 earthquake.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Although there are reports of an eruption at the time of the earthquake, most sources suggest that the volcano had been inactive since the destructive eruption of 1669.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Analysis of the relationship between eruptions and earthquakes has found that earthquakes are followed by long periods without activity in the 'rift zones' that extend out to north and south from the summit.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Estimates of Coulomb stress transfer due to the dyke intrusion in the rift zones associated with the 1669 eruption suggest that this could have helped to trigger the 1693 earthquake by increasing stress levels on the faults.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Despite the difficulty of separating the effects of this event from the mainshock, some information is available.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] This earthquake caused widespread damage, particularly in Augusta where almost half of the houses were destroyed.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Most of the buildings in two districts of Avola collapsed and many buildings were also destroyed in Noto, Floridia, Lentini and Mellili.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Some buildings collapsed in Catania, Vizzini and Sortini.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] There were an estimated 200 deaths in both Augusta and Noto.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The area of severe damage covered most of southeastern Sicily, an area of about 14,000 square kilometres (5,400 sq mi), including all the present provinces of Catania, Ragusa and Syracuse.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] At least 70 cities, towns and villages were devastated, with some examples of at least partial building collapse as far afield as Messina, Agrigento, Palermo, Reggio Calabria and Malta.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The earthquake also triggered large landslides, such as at Noto Antica and Sortino, and in one case a large rockslide dammed a stream, forming a lake a few kilometres long.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Several large northwest-southeast trending fractures were created up to 500 metres (1,600 ft) long and 2 metres (6.6 ft) wide, on the plains just south of Catania.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] In the same area, sand volcanoes were formed by jets of water spurting as much as several metres into the air, with similar phenomena being reported from the Lentini plain and along some river valleys.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] At Augusta the tsunami damaged galleys of the Knights of Malta that were anchored in the harbour when they were grounded during the initial withdrawal of the sea.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The number of deaths recorded at the time in official sources were about 12,000 in Catania (63% of the population), 5,045 in Ragusa (51%), 3,500 in Syracuse (23%) 3,000 in Noto (25%), 1,840 in Augusta (30%) and 3,400 in Modica (19%).
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The total death toll in the same source was recorded as 54,000 with other sources referring to totals of about 60,000.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] In 1853, Mallet recorded 93,000 deaths in his catalogue of earthquakes.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Sicily was at the time ruled as part of the Crown of Aragon by the Kings of Spain.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The Viceroy in Madrid, the Duke of Uceda, reacted by appointing Giuseppe Lanza, the Duke of Camastra, and the Prince of Aragon as Vicars General for the Val Demone and Val di Noto regions of Sicily respectively.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Due to illness, both the Prince of Aragon and his replacement the bishop of Syracuse were unable to take up the position of Vicar General for Val di Noto and the Duke of Camastra was forced to take on the responsibility for both areas.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Camastra already had considerable experience as an administrator, having served in a number of senior military and judicial positions.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The Viceroy also appointed three generals as commissioners in order to organise the immediate relief efforts in the worst affected cities.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] One of the Duke of Camastra's first acts was to temporarily exempt the worst affected areas from taxes.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Amongst other administrators sent to the damaged area was Colonel Don Carlos de Grunenbergh, royal engineer to the King of Spain, who had experience in planning and building fortifications.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] In Palermo, the Viceroy formed two councils, a civil one made up of nobles, and another that was ecclesiastical made up of senior church officials.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] They were directed to meet twice weekly and were charged with the drawing up of plans for the reconstruction of the worst affected towns and cities.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The initial reconstruction efforts concentrated on restoring the military defences of Syracuse, Augusta, Catania and Acireale, due to their strategic importance.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The reconstruction plans were of three types: move the town to a new site, rebuild at the same site with a completely new town plan or rebuild using the existing town plan.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Examples of towns that fell in the first category were Avola and Noto, their former locations now being known as Avola Antica and Noto Antica.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Catania is an example of a city that was rebuilt on the same site to a new plan while adapting some of the existing structures.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Syracuse is an example of a city rebuilt entirely to its existing plan.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Ragusa was partly rebuilt on its old site to the medieval plan (*Ragusa Ibla*) and partly on a new, but neighbouring site, to a 'modern' plan (*Ragusa Superiore*).
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] The degree and extent of the damage caused by the earthquake prompted an architectural revival in the towns of Sicily and Malta, a style that has become known as Sicilian Baroque.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] At this time many of the palazzi, public buildings, cathedrals and churches were reconstructed in this style.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Towns that suffered serious damage from the earthquake in which many of their structures were rebuilt, include Syracuse, Ragusa, Catania, Caltagirone, Palazzolo Acreide, Modica, Comiso, Scicli and Mdina on Malta.
[src:sicily/1693-sicily-earthquake] Many of these towns now form part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site *Late Baroque Towns of the Val di Noto (South-Eastern Sicily)*, inscribed in 1992, referring to the "exceptional quality" of the region's art and architecture.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] A devastating earthquake occurred on 28 December 1908 in Sicily and Calabria, southern Italy, with a moment magnitude of 7.1 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (*Extreme*).
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The epicentre was in the Strait of Messina which separates Sicily from the Italian mainland.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The cities of Messina and Reggio Calabria were nearly destroyed and around 120,000 people died, making it the deadliest earthquake in the history of Europe.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] According to Italy's National Institute of Geophysics and Vulcanology, the earthquake was caused by a large, low-angle SE-dipping, blind normal fault, lying mainly offshore in the Strait of Messina, between plates.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Its upper projection intersects the Earth's surface on the western side of the Strait, Sicily's coast.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In 2019 researchers at Birkbeck, University of London, discovered the active fault responsible for the earthquake.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The study, led by Marco Meschis, identified the fault as the previously mapped but little-studied Messina-Taormina Fault which lies off the Sicilian coast and runs the length of the Strait of Messina.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The team used data from 1907–1908 to examine the pattern of uplifts and subsidence observed in the Messina and Calabria area which bore a strong resemblance to those resulting from other powerful earthquakes triggered by normal faults.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] After comparing the direction and size of movements on well-known faults with the surface movements seen in Messina and Calabria, the researchers identified the probable active fault which caused the catastrophic earthquake as well as the direction and size of the movements.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Italy sits along the boundary zone of the African plate, and this plate is pushing against the sea floor underneath Europe at a rate of 25 millimetres (0.98 inches) per year.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] This causes vertical displacement, which can cause earthquakes.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The earthquake was recorded by 110 seismographic stations around the world, and was one of the first to be recorded by instruments.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Some of the strongest earthquakes of the last centuries occurred in the Calabrian Arc, such as the 1783 and 1905 Calabrian earthquakes, as well as the more catastrophic 1908 Messina earthquake.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Records indicate that considerable seismic activity occurred in the areas around the Strait of Messina for several months prior to 28 December; it increased in intensity beginning on 1 November.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] On 10 December, a magnitude 4 earthquake caused damage to a few buildings in Novara di Sicilia and Montalbano Elicona, both in the Province of Messina.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] A total of 293 aftershocks took place between 28 December 1908 and 11 March 1909.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In 2008, it was proposed that the concurrent tsunami was not generated by the earthquake, but rather by a large undersea landslide it had triggered.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The probable source of the tsunami was off Giardini Naxos (40 km south of Messina), on the Sicilian coast, where a large submarine landslide body with a headwall scarp was visible on a bathymetric map of the Ionian seafloor.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Another study attributed the source of the tsunami to having been a landslide which took place off of north-eastern Sicily and southern Calabria, most likely offshore between San Leo and Bocale in Calabria.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] On Monday, 28 December 1908, at 5:20:27 an earthquake of 7.1 on the moment magnitude scale occurred.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Its epicentre was in the Strait of Messina which separates the busy Sicilian port city of Messina from Reggio Calabria on the Italian mainland.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Its precise epicentre has been pinpointed in the northern Ionian Sea area close to the narrowest section of the Strait, the location of Messina.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] At least 91% of the structures in Messina were destroyed or irreparably damaged and 75,000 people were killed in the city and its suburbs.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Reggio Calabria and other locations in Calabria also suffered heavy damage, with some 25,000 people killed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Reggio's historic centre was almost completely eradicated.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The number of casualties is based on 1901 and 1911 census data.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] It was the most destructive earthquake in recorded history to strike Europe.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The ground shook for 37 seconds, and the damage was widespread, with destruction felt over a 4,300 km2 (1,700 sq mi) area.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In Calabria, the ground shook violently from Scilla to south of Reggio, provoking landslides inland in the Reggio area and along the sea-cliff from Scilla to Bagnara.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In the Calabrian commune of Palmi on the Tyrrhenian coast, there was devastation that left 600 dead.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Damage was also inflicted along the eastern Sicilian coast, but only Messina was hit as badly as Calabria.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The mesoseismal area was confined near the coast along a 1-to-4-kilometre-wide (0.6 to 2.5 mi) belt that shook Messina and the surrounding villages.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Catania, the largest city in eastern Sicily, did not incur notable damage.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Most accounts concur that it was the second upwards motion that caused the widespread destruction in Messina; the accompanying noise described as having been "exactly like that made by a fast train in a tunnel".
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The elevated death toll was due to the fact that most people were asleep, and killed outright or buried alive in their beds, as their houses collapsed on top of them.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Thousands were trapped under debris, and died from their injuries.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] One week before the earthquake, 160,000 inhabitants were counted in the entire Messina commune.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] On 28 December, Messina was even more crowded than usual, due to the number of overnight visitors from outlying areas who had come to the city to see a performance of Giuseppe Verdi's opera *Aida*, which had been staged the previous evening at the Vittorio Emanuele II theatre.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] About ten minutes after the earthquake, the sea on both sides of the Strait suddenly withdrew as a 12-meter (39-foot) tsunami swept in, and three waves struck nearby coasts.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] It struck hardest along the Calabrian coast and inundated Reggio Calabria after the sea had receded 70 metres (230 ft) from the shore.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The entire Reggio seafront was destroyed and people who had gathered there perished.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Nearby Villa San Giovanni was also badly hit.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Along the coast between Lazzaro and Pellaro, houses and a railway bridge were washed away.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In Messina, the tsunami also caused devastation and death; many of the survivors of the earthquake had fled to the relative safety of the seafront to escape their collapsing houses.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The second and third tsunami waves, coming in rapid succession and higher than the first, raced over the harbour, smashed boats docked at the pier, and broke parts of the sea wall.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] After engulfing the port and three city streets inland beyond the harbour, the waves swept away people, ships that had been anchored in the harbour, fishing boats and ferries, and inflicted further damage on the edifices within the zone which had remained standing after the shock.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The ships that were still attached to their moorings collided with one another but did not incur major damage.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Afterwards, Messina harbour was filled with floating wreckage and the corpses of drowned people and animals.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Towns and villages along the eastern coast of Sicily were assaulted by high waves which killed people and damaged boats and other property.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Two hours later, the tsunami struck Malta, rushing into Marsamxett Harbour and damaging property in Msida.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] About 2,000 people were killed by the tsunami in Messina on the eastern coast of Sicily, and in Reggio Calabria and its coastal environs.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Messina lost almost half its population and the entire historical city centre was devastated, including its Norman cathedral, which had withstood previous earthquakes such as a severe one in 1783; only its perimeter walls and apses remained standing.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Messina shoreline was irrevocably altered as large sections of the coast had sunk several feet into the sea.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Houses, churches, palaces and monuments, military barracks, commercial, municipal and public buildings had all collapsed entirely or were severely damaged.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Many structures were left as cracked shells: roofless, windowless and standing upright precariously.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Maurolico boarding school in Corso Cavour was pulverised, burying the students.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] A total of 348 railway workers were killed when the two railway stations crumbled.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The American consulate fronting the harbour was reduced to a pile of rubble; the British consulate sustained little outward damage (its flag still flew), but its interior was wrecked.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The French consul and his children also died, while his wife escaped.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Ethel Ogston, wife of the British vice-consul, died instantly after being struck by a falling balcony as she attempted to escape through the streets with her husband Alfred and her daughter, both of whom survived.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Former US vice-consul Joseph Pierce, who was the Messina correspondent for the Associated Press, and his family were crushed to death when their damaged home in Via Porta Real Basso, close to the harbour, was brought down by the force of the waves created by the tsunami.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Socialist historian Gaetano Salvemini survived but lost his wife, five children and sister.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Questore (Head of Police) Paolo Caruso died in his office, killed by a fallen beam.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Anglican priest and football pioneer Charles Bousfield Huleatt, along with his family and other players of the Messina Football Club, died.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Composer Riccardo Casalaina and his wife perished alongside one another in their bed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Tenor Angelo Gamba, who had performed on stage in *Aida* on the evening before the earthquake, also died, together with his wife and two sons, when the Hotel Europa collapsed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Hungarian soprano Paola Koraleck (who sang the role of Aida) was lying awake when the earthquake struck.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] She leapt from a window of the damaged Hotel Trinacria, breaking both arms in the fall.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The earthquake wrecked the commercial section along Messina's Corso Vittorio Emanuele that skirted the seafront.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] This included the elegant *Palazzata*, a long sequence of grand buildings that fronted the sickle-shaped harbour.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Palazzata had originally been built in baroque style in the seventeenth century, and was mainly the work of Simone Gullì.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Most of the baroque buildings had been destroyed in the earthquake of 1783, and had been rebuilt in neo-classical style in the early nineteenth century.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] It was the imposing neo-classical Palazzata, with some of the surviving baroque buildings, that was badly damaged in 1908.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The shaking was especially intense in the port area, resulting in the permanent displacement of the stone pavings in a "wave-like pattern".
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Damage was heaviest in the old historic centre and the low, level central and northern sections of the city, due to the soft sandy soil; it was less severe in the mountainous western part, as the structures were built on firmer terrain, such as the Gonzaga Fort, which was unscathed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The area between Cathedral Square and the 16th century Civic Hospital which fronted the Torrente Portalegni was obliterated; the adjacent Via Porta Imperiale was struck particularly hard on both sides.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Torrente Bocetta zone also received severe damage.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The 17th-century Real Cittadella, which guarded the harbour, was partially destroyed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Huge crevasses and fissures opened in the streets and these as well as the mounds of rubble, and falling masonry, hampered survivors who had fled from their razed homes to seek safety.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Two of the main thoroughfares Via Garibaldi and Corso Cavour were rendered impassable by the hillocks of rubble and debris 5 metres (16 ft) in height.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Families had become separated and a torrential downpour of rain that had begun only minutes before the earthquake added to the confusion, impeding visibility along with the darkness and thick clouds of dust.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The great gas tanks at the northern end of the city blew up, entombing living survivors and the already dead.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Fires broke out, caused by broken gas pipes, which added to the chaos and destruction.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The ground continued to shake with repeated aftershocks causing remaining structures to topple down onto the ruins of demolished edifices killing and injuring rescuers and those who had survived the mainshock.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Survivors described having seen horribly disfigured bodies and injured people badly maimed and screaming for help.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Cobbler Francesco Missiani and his family came upon two dying girls, both of whom had suffered appalling head and chest injuries.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Processions of naked survivors carrying pictures of saints appeared in the streets.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] People searched with bare hands through the debris for trapped loved ones.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Rescuers at the scene managed to save some people clinging precariously to gaping upper storeys, windows and teetering balconies by using ropes to pull them to safety.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Similar scenes of destruction were replicated in Reggio Calabria.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Its historical centre was eradicated and the monumental Aragonese Castle, one of the few edifices to have survived the 1783 earthquake, was badly damaged.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] With the exception of one mansion, all the structures in its principal thoroughfare Corso Garibaldi were destroyed including the Cathedral, municipal buildings and palazzi.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Only about 50 houses remained standing in Reggio.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The civilian and military hospitals in Messina, and the civic hospital in Reggio Calabria all lay in ruins with nearly all the doctors and nurses dead.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The injured in the two cities had no medical support or medicine until outside relief arrived and hospital tents were set up.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Telegraph lines had been severed and railway lines mangled, making communication impossible.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Most of Messina's officials were killed or gravely injured, along with almost the entire police force and soldiers of the garrison, who perished when their respective barracks collapsed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Many officers in the garrison survived, their accommodation being more substantial.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Prisoners who had escaped death when the prison fell began looting property and even robbing corpses of their jewellery.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In Reggio an estimated 1,800 convicts died when the prison was destroyed.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Peasants from nearby rural villages joined the looters.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Troops were soon sent to Messina and martial law was declared by General Feira Di Cossatto.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Rescuers searched through the ruins for weeks, and whole families were still being pulled out alive, days following the earthquake, but thousands remained buried beneath the rubble, their bodies never recovered.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Buildings in Messina had not been constructed for earthquake resistance, having been built out of small stones and carelessly-applied mortar with heavy tiled roofs, ornamental cornices, unsupported cross beams and vulnerable foundations on soft soil.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The most populous areas in the city were concentrated in and around Via dei Monasteri (today Via XXIV Maggio), Via Casa Pia (today Via Monsignor D'Arrigo) and Via Porta Imperiale; all of which were located in the historic city centre.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In addition to the poorly constructed buildings, the widespread destruction in Messina and Reggio Calabria was due to the telluric movement having been so close to the surface.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] News of the disaster was carried to Prime Minister Giovanni Giolitti by Italian torpedo boats which set out from Messina to Nicotera, where the telegraph lines were still working, but that was not accomplished until midnight at the end of the day.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Rail lines in the area had been destroyed, often along with the railway stations.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Pope Pius X filled the Apostolic Palace with refugees.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Italian navy and army responded and began searching, treating the injured, providing food and water, and evacuating refugees (as did every ship).
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Giolitti imposed martial law under the direction of General Francesco Mazza with all looters to be shot on sight, which occasionally extended to survivors foraging for food and searching through the rubble for trapped family members.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] King Victor Emmanuel III and Queen Elena arrived two days after the earthquake to assist the victims and survivors.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The disaster made headlines worldwide and international relief efforts were launched.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] With the help of the Red Cross and sailors of the Russian and British fleets, search and cleanup were expedited.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The French battleships *Justice* and *Vérité*, and three torpedo boat destroyers were ordered to Messina.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Navy's Great White Fleet, USS *Connecticut* and *Illinois*, along with supply ships USS *Celtic* and USS *Culgoa* also delivered succor.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The American supply vessels including the tender USS *Yankton*, buttressed with extra medical personnel and supplies from the battleship fleet, delivered supplies to help the refugees and remained on station giving medical aid.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The King of Italy later awarded a commemorative medal for 1908 earthquake assistance, struck in gold, silver and bronze.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Several streets in Messina have been named after the Russian sailors, including Largo dei Marinai Russi.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In 2012, a monument to the Russian sailors, designed by Pietro Kufferle in 1911, was installed in the city, and a bust of Emperor Nicholas II was opened in Taormina; a bust of Admiral Fyodor Ushakov was set up in 2013.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] When the reconstruction of Messina began from 1909, authorities mandated architecture able to withstand earthquakes of variable magnitude.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Initially, a plan was adopted to demolish the remaining structures of Messina and to transfer the city and its port elsewhere in Sicily, but strong protests from the Messinesi led to the discarding of this suggestion.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The Real Cittadella, Vittorio Emanuele theatre, sections of the Matagrifone castle and Monti di Pieta remained standing but sustained considerable damage.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The 16th-century Church of Ringo in the fishermen's quarter of the same name along the northern Messina riviera withstood the shock and survives to date.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The "Scalinata Santa Barbara", large sections of the Muro Carlo V and a number of 18th and 19th century houses in the ancient quarter of Tirone survived; additionally several houses in Via Fata Morgana and Via Giordano Bruno remained standing and are in use today.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Although some of the dwellings (known as *le mignuni* in local dialect) located in the slum of Avignone also remained standing relatively intact, they have since been demolished.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In Reggio Calabria the Palazzo Nesci was one of the few 19th-century structures to withstand the earthquake.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The new city of Messina was constructed on the rubble of the old city using the plan of a modern layout of a "city regularly cut up like a checker board" with buildings of uniform size and height as presented in 1911 by architect Luigi Borzì (1853–1919).
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] This necessitated the demolition of buildings that were salvageable but did not conform to the new urban plan.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] These included the Palazzata, Baroque San Gregorio church situated above Via Monasteri and the 18th century Chiesa delle Anime del Purgatorio located in Via Cardines and Largo Purgatorio.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The latter church was badly damaged but principally in the apsidal section and was reparable.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] It was demolished to extend Via Garibaldi in a southerly direction.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In the wake of the earthquake, many of the homeless residents of Messina and Calabria were relocated to various parts of Sicily and other regions of mainland Italy.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] In 1909, the SS *Florida*, carrying 850 emigrants from Naples, collided in a fog with RMS *Republic*.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Three people aboard the *Florida* died in the collision.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The passengers descended into panic and the captain had to shoot in the air to calm them down.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The ship was eventually rescued and arrived in New York.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] A 2025 study examined whether the earthquake prompted increased emigration to the United States, finding no evidence of a substantial increase in emigration following the earthquake.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] The disaster affected the local economy and Messina faced a temporary depopulation after so many homeless survivors had sought refuge elsewhere, in particular Catania and Palermo where a large number found work as artisans.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] It has been estimated that only 19,000 remained with just 2000 in the old city center.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] However, there was soon a huge influx of migrants, mostly from nearby Sicilian and Calabrian localities who were needed as necessary labourers for the reconstruction.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] According to the 1911 census the population of Messina had increased to 127,000.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Among these were many Messinesi who had returned to their native city.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Men notably outnumbered the women which resulted in a decrease in marriages.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] As late as 2021, families were still living in the wooden barracks in zones known as *Baraccopoli* which were erected in 1909 to provide temporary housing for the homeless survivors.
[src:sicily/1908-messina-earthquake] Because of its dearth of historical buildings due to the catastrophic 1908 earthquake, as well as the 1943 Allied bombardment during World War II, Messina has been called "the city without memory".
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An institutional referendum (Italian: *referendum istituzionale*, or *referendum sulla forma istituzionale dello Stato*) was held by universal suffrage in the Kingdom of Italy on 2 June 1946, a key event of contemporary Italian history.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until 1946, Italy was a kingdom ruled by the House of Savoy, reigning since the unification of Italy in 1861 and previously rulers of the Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1922, the rise of Benito Mussolini and the creation of the Fascist regime in Italy, which eventually resulted in engaging the country in World War II alongside Nazi Germany, considerably weakened the role of the royal house.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the Italian Civil War and the Liberation of Italy from Axis troops in 1945, a popular referendum on the institutional form of the state was called the next year and resulted in voters choosing the replacement of the monarchy with a republic.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The 1946 Italian general election to elect the Constituent Assembly of Italy was held on the same day.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As with the simultaneous Constituent Assembly elections, the referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The results were proclaimed by the Supreme Court of Cassation on 10 June 1946: 12,717,923 citizens in favor of the republic and 10,719,284 citizens in favor of the monarchy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The event is commemorated annually by the *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the entry into force of the new Constitution of the Italian Republic, on 1 January 1948, Enrico De Nicola became the first to assume the functions of president of Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It marked the first time that most of the Italian Peninsula was under a single republican government since the fall of the Roman Republic.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the history of Italy there are several so-called "republican" governments that have followed one another over time.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Examples are the ancient Roman Republic and the medieval maritime republics.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From Cicero to Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian philosophers have imagined the foundations of political science and republicanism.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But it was Giuseppe Mazzini who revived the republican idea in Italy in the 19th century.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An Italian nationalist in the historical radical tradition and a proponent of a republicanism of social-democratic inspiration, Mazzini helped define the modern European movement for popular democracy in a republican state.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mazzini formulated a concept known as "thought and action" in which thought and action must be joined and every thought must be followed by action, therefore rejecting intellectualism and the notion of divorcing theory from practice.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The foundation of the Young Italy constitutes a key moment of the Italian Risorgimento and this republican program precedes in time the proposals for the unification of Italy of Vincenzo Gioberti and Cesare Balbo, aimed at reunifying the Italian territory under the presidency of the Pope.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Subsequently, the philosopher Carlo Cattaneo promoted a secular and republican Italy in the extension of Mazzini's ideas, but organized as a federal republic.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political projects of Mazzini and Cattaneo were thwarted by the action of the Piedmontese Prime Minister Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, and Giuseppe Garibaldi.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The latter set aside his republican ideas to favor Italian unity.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After having obtained the conquest of the whole of southern Italy during the Expedition of the Thousand, Garibaldi handed over the conquered territories to the king of Sardinia Victor Emmanuel II, which were annexed to the Kingdom of Sardinia after a plebiscite.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This earned him heavy criticism from numerous republicans who accused him of treason.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] While a laborious administrative unification began, a first Italian parliament was elected and, on 17 March 1861, Victor Emmanuel II was proclaimed king of Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From 1861 to 1946, Italy was a constitutional monarchy founded on the Albertine Statute, named after the king who promulgated it in 1848, Charles Albert of Sardinia.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The parliament included a Senate, whose members were appointed by the king, and a Chamber of Deputies, elected by census vote.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1861 only 2% of Italians had the right to vote.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the political panorama of the time there was a republican political movement which had its martyrs, such as the soldier Pietro Barsanti.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Barsanti was a supporter of republican ideas, and was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army with the rank of corporal.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was sentenced to death and shot in 1870 for having favored an insurrectional attempt against the Savoy monarchy and is therefore considered the first martyr of the modern Italian Republic and a symbol of republican ideals in Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The balance of power between the Chamber and Senate initially shifted in favor of the Senate, composed mainly of nobles and industrial figures.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Little by little, the Chamber of Deputies took on more and more importance with the evolution of the bourgeoisie and the large landowners, concerned with economic progress, but supporters of order and a certain social conservatism.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republicans took part in the elections to the Italian Parliament, and in 1853 they formed the Action Party around Giuseppe Mazzini.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although in exile, Mazzini was elected in 1866, but refused to take his seat in parliament.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Carlo Cattaneo was elected deputy in 1860 and 1867, but refused so as not to have to swear loyalty to the House of Savoy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The problem of the oath of loyalty to the monarchy, necessary to be elected, was the subject of controversy within the republican forces.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1873 Felice Cavallotti, one of the most committed Italian politicians against the monarchy, preceded his oath with a declaration in which he reaffirmed his republican beliefs.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1882, a new electoral law lowered the census limit for voting rights, increasing the number of voters to over two million, equal to 7% of the population.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the same year the Italian Workers' Party was created, which in 1895 became the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1895 the intransigent republicans agreed to participate in the political life of the Kingdom, establishing the Italian Republican Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two years later, the far left reached its historical maximum level in Parliament with 81 deputies, for the three radical-democratic, socialist components and Republican.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the death of Felice Cavallotti in 1898, the radical left gave up on posing the institutional problem.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Italian politics, the socialist party progressively divided into two tendencies: a maximalist one, led among others by Arturo Labriola and Enrico Ferri, and supporting the use of strikes; the other, reformist and pro-government, was led by Filippo Turati.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A nationalist movement emerged, led in particular by Enrico Corradini, as well as a Catholic social and democratic movement, the National Democratic League, led by Romolo Murri.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1904, Pope Pius X authorized Catholics to participate individually in political life, but in 1909 he condemned the National Democratic League created by Romolo Murri, who was excommunicated.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Finally, a law of 3 June 1912 marked Italy's evolution towards a certain political liberalism by establishing universal male suffrage.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Italy began to be counted among the world's liberal democracies.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After World War I, Italian political life was animated by four great movements.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two of these movements were in favor of democratic development within the framework of existing monarchical institutions: the reformist socialists and the Italian People's Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two other movements challenged these institutions: the Republican Party on the one hand, and the maximalist socialists.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1919 elections, the parties most imbued with republican ideology (the maximalist socialists and the Republican Party) won, obtaining 165 out of 508 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1921 elections, after the foundation of the Italian Communist Party, the three parties republican, maximalist socialist and communist obtained 145 deputies out of 535.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Overall, at the beginning of the interwar period, less than 30% of those elected were in favor of the establishment of a republican regime.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In this context, the rise of Benito Mussolini's fascist movement was based on the bitterness generated by the "mutilated victory", the fear of social unrest and the rejection of revolutionary, republican and Marxist ideology.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The liberal political system and part of the aristocracy chose to erect fascism as a bulwark against, in their way of seeing, these dangers.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In October 1922, the nomination of Benito Mussolini as prime minister by King Victor Emmanuel III, following the march on Rome, paved the way for the establishment of the dictatorship.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Albertine Statute was progressively emptied of its content.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Parliament was subject to the will of the new government.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 June 1924, 127 deputies left Parliament and retreated to the Aventine Hill, a clumsy maneuver which, in effect, left the field open to the fascists.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] They then had the fate of Italy in their hands for two decades.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Not only did Victor Emmanuel III appeal to Mussolini to form the government in 1922 and allow him to proceed with the domestication of Parliament, but he did not even draw the consequences of the assassination of Giacomo Matteotti in 1924.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He accepted the title of emperor in 1936 at the end of Second Italo-Ethiopian War, then the alliance with Nazi Germany and Italy's entry into World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the implementation of fascist laws (Royal Decree of 6 November 1926), all political parties operating on Italian territory were dissolved, with the exception of the National Fascist Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some of these parties expatriated and reconstituted themselves abroad, especially in France.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some movements remained outside, including the Italian Communist Party, the popular Catholic movement and other liberal movements.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This coalition dissolved on 5 May 1934 and, in August of the same year, the pact of unity of action was signed between the Italian Socialist Party and the Italian Communist Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the meantime, in Italy, clandestine anti-fascist nuclei were formed, in particular in Milan with Ferruccio Parri and in Florence with Riccardo Bauer.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Under the impetus of these groups, the Action Party, Mazzini's former republican party, was re-established.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Between the end of 1942 and the beginning of 1943, Alcide De Gasperi wrote *The reconstructive ideas of Christian Democracy*, which laid the foundations of the new Catholic-inspired party, the Christian Democracy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It brought together the veterans of Luigi Sturzo's Italian People's Party and the young people of Catholic associations, in particular of the University Federation.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 July 1943, the Allies landed in Sicily in Operation Husky.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 25 July 1943, Victor Emmanuel III revoked Mussolini's mandate as prime minister and had him arrested, entrusting the government to Marshal Pietro Badoglio.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The new government contacted the Allies to reach an armistice.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] When the Armistice of Cassibile was announced on 8 September 1943, the Germans reacted by placing under their control all the part of Italian territory that still escaped the Allied advance and by disarming the Italian Royal Army.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Victor Emmanuel III and Badoglio's government fled Rome and reached Brindisi, in southern Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In these dramatic circumstances, in the two territories the civil administration gave way to a military and police administration.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the parties that existed before fascism were reconstituted, alongside new political parties.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 9 September 1943, in Rome (still occupied by the Germans), a National Liberation Committee (CLN) was created, which brought together the parties and movements opposed to fascism and German occupation.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It was made up of representatives of the Italian Communist Party, members of the Action Party, Christian Democrats, liberals, socialists and progressive democrats.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The patriotic war of liberation led by the National Liberation Committee was also, for a significant part of its supporters, a war of social liberation, a war against a collaborationist elite.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the Americans and English, anxious to prepare for the post-war period, facilitated the entry into German-occupied territory of Italian democratic and republican activists aimed at counterbalancing the communist influence in the leadership of the National Liberation Committee.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This was the case, for example, of Leo Valiani, future member of the triumvirate responsible for the partisan insurrection in Piedmont and Lombardy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 31 March 1944, in Salerno, Palmiro Togliatti, general secretary of the Italian Communist Party, called for the formation of a government of national unity and no longer required the king's abdication as a prerequisite.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This declaration pushed the parties of the National Liberation Committee to rally around a compromise drawn up by Enrico De Nicola, president of the Chamber of Deputies until 1924, by Benedetto Croce of the liberal party and by the king's entourage.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As foreseen in this agreement, upon the liberation of Rome, on 4 June 1944, Victor Emmanuel III proclaimed his son Umberto lieutenant general of the kingdom, and the parties took political control of the nation, even if the war continued, stabilizing on the front on the Gothic line until April 1945.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From June 1944 to December 1945, three provisional coalition governments followed one another.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The first was led by Ivanoe Bonomi, of the Labour Democratic Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] His government included the anti-fascist liberals Carlo Sforza and Benedetto Croce, as well as Palmiro Togliatti.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although temporarily put aside, the question of Italian institutions remained one of the main open political questions.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Most of the forces supporting the National Liberation Committee were openly republicans and believed that the monarchy, in particular Victor Emmanuel III, had had a responsibility in the success of the fascist movement.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final agreement between the parties was to ask that at the end of the war, as soon as conditions were favourable, the calling of elections, an institutional referendum and the formation of a constituent assembly.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until then, on 31 January 1945, the Council of Ministers, chaired by Ivanoe Bonomi, issued a decree which recognized women's right to vote.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Universal suffrage was thus recognized, after the vain attempts made in 1881 and 1907 by women of the various parties.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Bonomi governments (II then III) were succeeded by the Parri government in June 1945, then by the First De Gasperi government in December 1945.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The question of the future form of the state, monarchy or republic, absorbed the minds of political circles.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The majority of Christian Democratic activists, especially young people, increasingly distanced themselves from the monarchy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During the local meetings of the leaders of this party, in Rome and Milan, motions were presented aimed at making official a political line favorable to a democratic republic.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The central political office tried to curb these pressures and maintain an intermediate position.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 16 March 1946, Prince Umberto decreed, as expected in 1944, that the question of the institutional form of the state would be decided by a referendum organized simultaneously with the election of a constituent assembly.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation was responsible for examining the appeals.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Its role was to be limited to observing the progress of voting operations and consolidating the bulletins issued by the offices that communicated the results in each constituency.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The counting of the ballots of the candidates for the constituent assembly had to precede that of the referendum.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] If the monarchy had won, it would have been the Constituent Assembly that would have had to choose the head of state.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Wanted by the Allies to verify that the conditions existed for voting in a country torn apart by the civil war only a few months earlier, partial municipal and provincial elections were held in March and April 1946 in half of the Italian municipalities and provinces.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These elections, which mainly involved left-wing cities, brought out three parties, with a clear advantage for the Christian Democrats, led by Alcide De Gasperi, which exceeded the sum of votes cast for the Italian Communist Party and the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After these administrative elections, the monarchists, already worried about the outcome of the referendum, became even more discouraged.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But a political event changed the situation during the referendum campaign.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A month before the referendum, Victor Emmanuel III abdicated in favor of his son Umberto, who was proclaimed king and took the name Umberto II.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The act of abdication, drawn up privately, is dated 9 May 1946.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This abdication was desired by the monarchists, since the crown prince was less compromised than his father in Mussolini's rise to power and in coexistence with the fascist forces.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is also possible that the command of the allied forces present on Italian territory encouraged the sovereign to abdicate in favor of his son.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former king immediately left Italy for Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Umberto II confirmed his promise to respect the popular decision regarding the referendum.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The representatives of the parties in favor of the Republic protested, arguing the assumption of royal powers by the lieutenant general conflicted with an article of the legislative decree of 16 March 1946 that aimed at guaranteeing institutional stability before the announcement of the results.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For observers, the gap between republicans and monarchists was narrowing, which increased tension in the final phase of the electoral campaign.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, some scuffles broke out between activists of the two sides in the tense climate.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The vote for the choice between monarchy or republic took place on 2 June and on the morning of 3 June 1946.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the transfer of the electoral cards from all of Italy and the minutes of the 31 constituencies to Rome, the results were expected on 8 June.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 June, the still provisional results were announced, and the final ones were communicated later due to missing data in some polling stations and after the examination of numerous appeals regarding the contested referendum ballots.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, 21,000 disputes occurred over the referendum ballots, most of which were quickly resolved.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the period of uncertainty between the end of the vote and the final official announcement of the results only strengthened tensions in the country.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the city of Naples, in Apulia, in Calabria and in Sicily, the monarchists carried out protest demonstrations, sometimes violent.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 7 June, a monarchist student, soon transformed into a martyr, was killed.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] One of the complaints submitted to the Supreme Court of Cassation is particularly delicate.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This controversy was over the definition of "majority".
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The monarchists believed that it was necessary to take into account not the majority of votes cast, but the "majority of electors", as an article of the electoral law provided.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The public prosecutor of the Supreme Court of Cassation, Massimo Pilotti, deemed this appeal admissible.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In his indictment Pilotti believed that the spirit and letter of the decrees as well as jurisprudence provide for the counting of voters, without excluding blank or invalid ballots.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But the Supreme Court of Cassation ruled against him, with 12 votes against to 7.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the one hand, it was believed that the vote, as a legal act, manifested a will and that the blank or null vote could be assimilated to the absence of expression of will.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation also identified another decree which specified that only "validly cast" votes should be preserved.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation finally announced that no law or decree dealt with the need for an absolute majority.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final results were announced on 18 June 1946.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 89%, with 54% of the votes cast for the republic and 46% for the monarchy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The analysis of the data by region showed an Italy practically divided in two: in the north the republic won with 66% of the votes cast, and the monarchy in the south with 64% of the votes.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, some voters were unable to vote.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Before the closure of the electoral lists in April 1945, many Italian soldiers were still outside the national territory, in detention or internment camps abroad.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These provinces, however, were all located in the north of the country, an area where the Republican vote obtained a fairly large majority.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The conservative, rural *Mezzogiorno* (southern Italy) region voted solidly for the monarchy (63.8%) while the more urbanised and industrialised *Nord* (northern Italy) voted equally firmly for a republic (66.2%).
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At first glance, the referendum seemed to simply divide Italy in two, between North and South, but the situation was more complex.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For example, the districts located to the north of Rome gave the majority to the republic, while those located to the south chose the monarchy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The electoral college of Rome was very divided and gave a slight majority to the choice of the monarchic regime.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican choice turned into a plebiscite, with over 80% of the votes cast in the electoral college of Bologna, and even more in that of Trento.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the South, however, the monarchist choice reached nearly 80% in the college of Naples.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But, in other regions, the vote was very fragmented.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There was not a total break with the past, but an interference between the two possible choices, which was expressed everywhere.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The occupation of the North by the German forces and the period of the Italian Civil War, with the fascist forces, undoubtedly favored an increase in the importance of the socialist and communist parties in this region, which were republican in tendency.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During these dark years, the populations concerned placed part of their hopes in dreams of revolution, or at least of change.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The South, not having experienced this situation and having welcomed King Victor Emmanuel III and his government, was perhaps more wary of these parties and placed its trust in the monarchic regime, preferring continuity to the "leap into the unknown" represented by the republican form.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Furthermore, the clientelism prevalent in the South favored a vote that tended to be conservative, and therefore monarchist.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some analysts also cite the influence of the Catholic Church or the Catholic press.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Other authors have highlighted more structural factors, such as differences in family organization or production by region.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Thus Carlo Bacetti compared, in Tuscany, the importance of metayage in the organization of work on the land, and the weight of the Communist Party in this region, which had republican tendencies.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At the same time, republican demonstrations took place in many cities.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Milanese newspaper, *Corriere della Sera*, on Tuesday 11 June, ran the headline: "The Italian Republic is born".
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] *La Stampa*, a Turin daily newspaper, declared more soberly: "The government confirms the victory of the republicans", and completed its coverage by asking: "the question is whether the republic has been proclaimed or not".
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Naples, a city with a population largely supportive of the monarchy, an incident occurred on 11 June.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A procession of supporters of the monarchy advanced towards the municipal buildings and then changed objective and headed towards the headquarters of the Italian Communist Party.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The crowd saw a red flag, but also a tricolor flag from which the royal coat of arms had been cut.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Despite the presence of armored vehicles, the demonstrators attempted to storm the communist party headquarters.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Protesters and law enforcement officers exchange gunfire.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] According to the prefect's report, the demonstrators shot first.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In any case the response was deadly, with machine gun fire.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There were nine deaths among royalist demonstrators and a large number of injuries.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Calm returned to the city only on 13 June.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the night of 12 June, the government met at Alcide De Gasperi's invitation.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister received a written communication from the King, in which he said he was ready to respect the verdict of the electors' vote, but adding that he would await the final declaration of the Supreme Court of Cassation.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The letter and the protests of the monarchists, like the bloody events of the day before in Naples, as well as the new demonstrations announced by the monarchists worried the ministers.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister collected all the votes of the government members, with the exception of the liberal minister Leone Cattani.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although some members of his entourage encouraged him to oppose this decision, the king, informed, decided to leave the country the following day, thus making a peaceful transfer of power possible, not without having denounced De Gasperi's "revolutionary gesture".
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He went into exile in Cascais, Portugal.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the same day as the former king's departure, the flag of Italy with the Savoy coat of arms in the centre was lowered from the Quirinal Palace.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Italian flag was modified with the decree of the president of the Council of Ministers No.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Compared to the monarchic banner, the Savoy coat of arms was eliminated.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican tricolour was then officially and solemnly delivered to the Italian military corps on 4 November 1947 on the occasion of National Unity and Armed Forces Day.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The universally adopted ratio is 2:3, while the war flag is squared (1:1).
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Each *comune* also has a *gonfalone* bearing its coat of arms.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 May 1949, a law was passed that described and regulated the way the flag was displayed outside public buildings and during national holidays.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the birth of the Italian Republic, "La leggenda del Piave" was temporarily chosen as the provisional national anthem, which replaced "Marcia Reale", the national anthem of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political class of the time then approved the proposal of the War Minister Cipriano Facchinetti, who foresaw the adoption of "Il Canto degli Italiani" as a provisional anthem of the State.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] "Il Canto degli Italiani" was therefore chosen, on 12 October 1946, as the provisional national anthem, a role that it later preserved while remaining the de facto anthem of the Italian Republic.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Over the decades there were several unsuccessful attempts to make it the official national anthem, until it finally gained official status on 4 December 2017.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 18 June 1946 at 6 pm, in the Sala della Lupa of Palazzo Montecitorio in Rome, the Supreme Court of Cassation proceeded to proclaim the results of the referendum, without accompanying this formalization with reservations as it had done previously.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the first session of the Constituent Assembly, on 28 June 1946, Enrico De Nicola was elected provisional head of the State, in the first round with 396 votes out of 501.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In addition to his personal qualities, the choice of a man born in Naples and long monarchic history, it was a sign of pacification and union towards the populations of southern Italy, in this accelerated transition towards the Republic.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was initially only provisional head of state and not president of Italy, since the latter did not yet have a constitution.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Alcide De Gasperi resigned and then regained the task of forming a new government, thus becoming the last Prime Minister of the monarchic era and the first of republican Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 1 January 1948, the Republican Constitution came into force, the content of which was discussed within the Constituent Assembly.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It proclaims in particular that "Italy is a democratic republic founded on labour" and that "the former kings of the House of Savoy, their wives and their male descendants are prohibited from entering and staying in the national territory".
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Enrico De Nicola then assumed the title of President of Italy.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The validity of the provision that prohibited the entry in Italy of some members of the House of Savoy ceased with the entry into force of the Constitutional Law of 23 October 2002, No.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 1, after a debate in parliament and in the country that lasted many years and Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples, son of King Umberto II, was able to enter Italy with his family already in the following December for a short visit.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former queen Marie-José had already been authorized to return to Italy in 1987 since, with the death of her husband Umberto II and having become a widow, her status as "spouse" was recognized as having ceased.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The photo, which later became a "symbol" of the celebrations for the outcome of the referendum, portrays the face of a young woman emerging from a copy of *Il Corriere della Sera* of 6 June 1946 with the title «*È nata la Repubblica Italiana*» ("The Italian Republic is born").
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The symbolic photo of the birth of the Republic was taken by Federico Patellani for the weekly *Tempo* (n.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 22, 15–22 June 1946) as part of a photo shoot celebrating the Republic and the new role of women; it was also featured on the front page of the *Il Corriere della Sera* itself and was later reused in many campaigns and posters.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Only in 2016 was the woman identified as Anna Iberti (1922–1997).
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the playing of the National Anthem *Il Canto degli Italiani*, the Frecce Tricolori cross the skies of Rome.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is tradition, for the members of the Italian government and for the presidents of the two chambers of parliament, to have pinned on their jacket, during the whole ceremony, an Italian tricolor cockade.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the anthem, the military parade begins, which the ground columns of military personnel saluting the President with eyes left or right with their colours dipped as they march past the dais.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mobile column crew contingent colour guards perform the salute in a like manner.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The military parade also includes some military delegations from the United Nations, NATO, the European Union and representatives of multinational departments with an Italian component.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the holiday, at the Quirinale Palace, the Changing of the Guard with the Corazzieri Regiment and the Fanfare of the Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment in high uniform is carried out in solemn form.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This solemn rite is only performed on two other occasions, during the celebrations of the Tricolour Day (7 January) and the National Unity and Armed Forces Day (4 November).
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Official ceremonies are held throughout the national territory.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Among them are the traditional receptions organized by each prefecture for the local authorities, which are preceded by solemn public demonstrations with reduced military parades that have been reviewed by the prefect in his capacity as the highest governmental authority in the province.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Similar ceremonies are also organized by the Regions and Municipalities.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] All over the world, Italian embassies organize ceremonies to which the Heads of State of the host country are invited.
[src:sicily/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Greetings from the other Heads of State reach the President of Italy from all over the world.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The **1990 FIFA World Cup** was the 14th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was held from 8 June to 8 July 1990 in Italy, the second country to host the event for a second time (after Mexico in 1986).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams representing 116 national football associations entered and qualification began in April 1988.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Twenty-two teams qualified from this process, along with the host nation Italy and defending champions Argentina.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament was won by West Germany, for the third time.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat defending champions Argentina 1–0 at the Stadio Olimpico in Rome, a rematch of the previous final four years earlier.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy finished third and England fourth, after both lost their semi-finals in penalty shootouts.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Costa Rica, Ireland and the United Arab Emirates made their first appearances in the finals.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the only time the United Arab Emirates qualified for a FIFA World Cup finals.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon went on an unexpectedly strong run in the tournament, becoming the first African team to reach the quarter-finals of the World Cup.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The official match ball was the Adidas Etrusco Unico.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1990 World Cup is widely regarded as one of the poorest World Cups in terms of the games.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It generated an average 2.21 goals per game – a record low that still stands – and a then-record 16 red cards, including the first dismissal in a final.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, the tournament had a significant lasting influence on the game as a whole.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In England, the team's success in this tournament led to the resurgence of the domestic top-flight, which had suffered from violence on the pitch and hooliganism by spectators throughout the 1980s.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It saw the introduction of the pre-match Fair Play Flag (then inscribed with "Fair Play Please") to encourage fair play.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Overly defensive tactics of many teams led to the introduction of the back-pass rule in 1992 and three points for a win instead of two, both of which have encouraged attacking play, increasing spectator interest in the sport.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1990 World Cup stands as one of the most watched events in television history, garnering an estimated 26.69 billion non-unique viewers over the course of the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the first World Cup officially recorded and transmitted in HDTV, which was a joint effort of the Italian broadcaster RAI and Japan's NHK.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The huge success of the broadcasting model also had a lasting impact on the sport.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] At the time, it was the most watched World Cup in history in non-unique viewers, later bettered only by the 1994 and the 2002 editions of the competition.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The vote to choose the hosts of the 1990 tournament was held on 19 May 1984 in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Here, the FIFA Executive Committee chose Italy ahead of the only rival bid, the USSR, by 11 votes to 5.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This awarding made Italy only the second nation to host two World Cup tournaments after Mexico had also achieved this with their 1986 staging, having agreed to replace Colombia as hosts the year before the 1990 hosts were chosen.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy had previously held the event in 1934, where they had won their first championship.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Austria, England, France, Greece, West Germany and Yugoslavia also submitted initial applications for the 31 July 1983 deadline.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A month later, only England, Greece, Italy and the Soviet Union remained in the hunt after the other contenders all withdrew.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] All four bids were assessed by FIFA in late 1983, with the final decision over-running into 1984 due to the volume of paperwork involved.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In early 1984, England and Greece also withdrew, leading to a two-horse race in the final vote.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet boycott of the 1984 Olympic Games, announced on the eve of the World Cup decision, was speculated to have been a major factor behind Italy winning the vote so decisively, although this was denied by the FIFA President João Havelange.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet state media responded by accusing FIFA of political corruption, and blamed the organisation's American sponsors (chiefly Coca-Cola) for influencing the decision.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Iran also planned to host the competition.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They proposed it to FIFA in 1977, but a few months later they withdrew their request.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] 116 teams entered the 1990 World Cup, including Italy as host nation and Argentina as reigning World Cup champions, who were both granted automatic qualification.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thus, the remaining 22 finals places were divided among the continental confederations, with 114 initially entering the qualification competition.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Due to rejected entries and withdrawals, 103 teams eventually participated in the qualifying stages.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thirteen places were contested by UEFA teams (Europe), two by CONMEBOL teams (South America), two by CAF teams (Africa), two by AFC teams (Asia), and two by CONCACAF teams (North and Central America and Caribbean).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The remaining place was decided by a play-off between a CONMEBOL team and a team from the OFC (Oceania).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After finishing in third place in 1986, France missed the tournament for the first time since the 1974 edition.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Mexico was disqualified during the qualification process for fielding four overage players in a prior youth tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three teams made their debuts; this was the first World Cup to feature Costa Rica, the Republic of Ireland, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Austria, Cameroon, Czechoslovakia and Yugoslavia also returned after missing the 1986 tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the only time the United Arab Emirates qualified for the World Cup finals and the last time Mexico did not participate in the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Twelve stadiums in twelve cities were selected to host matches at the 1990 World Cup.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Stadio San Nicola in Bari and Turin's Stadio delle Alpi were completely new venues opened for the World Cup.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Of the twelve stadiums used, only four (San Siro, Luigi Ferraris, Comunale of Florence, and Renato Dall'Ara) had been used for the 1934 FIFA World Cup, while Trieste was the only host city from 1934 not to be selected for the 1990 tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ten existing venues all underwent extensive programmes of improvements in preparation for the tournament, forcing many of the club tenants of the stadia to move to temporary homes.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Additional seating and roofs were added to most stadia, with further redevelopments seeing running tracks removed and new pitches laid.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Due to structural constraints, several of the existing stadia had to be virtually rebuilt to implement the changes required.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Like España '82 and México '86, the group stage of this tournament was organised so an individual group only played in two cities in close proximity to each other.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group A only played in Rome and Florence (hosts Italy played all but two competitive matches in Rome: their semi-final match was played in Napoli, and their match for third place in Bari), Group B played their matches in Naples and Bari (except for Argentina vs.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon, which was the opening match of the tournament, played in Milan), Group C played their matches in Turin and Genoa, Group D played all their matches in Milan and Bologna, Group E played only in Udine and Verona, and Group F played in the insular cities of Cagliari and Palermo.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The cities that hosted the most World Cup matches were the two biggest cities in Italy: Rome and Milan, each hosting six matches, and Bari, Naples, and Turin each hosted five matches.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cagliari, Udine and Palermo were the only cities of the 12 selected that did not host any knockout round matches.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The England national team, at the British government's request, played all 3 of their group stage matches in Cagliari on the island of Sardinia.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hooliganism, rife in English football in the 1980s had spilled over onto the European continent when 39 mostly Italian Juventus supporters were killed and 600 were injured at the 1985 European Cup Final in Brussels while trying to flee from an attack by Liverpool supporters.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Italian authorities' presence proved to be justified as there were several riots during the time England were playing their matches in Cagliari, leading to a number of injuries, arrests and even deportations.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Most of the construction cost in excess of their original estimates and total costs ended up being over £550 million (approximately $935 million).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Rome's Stadio Olimpico which hosted the final was the most expensive project overall, while Udine's Stadio Friuli, the newest of the existing stadia (opened 14 years prior), cost the least to redevelop.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Squads for the 1990 World Cup consisted of 22 players, as for the previous tournament in 1986.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Replacement of injured players was permitted during the tournament at FIFA's discretion.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two goalkeepers – Argentina's Ángel Comizzo and England's Dave Beasant – entered their respective squads during the tournament to replace injured players (Nery Pumpido and David Seaman).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] 41 match officials from 34 countries were assigned to the tournament to serve as referees and assistant referees.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Officials in italics were only used as assistants during the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Referees dressed only in traditional black jerseys for the final time at a World Cup (a red change shirt was used for two Group C games in which Scotland wore their navy blue shirts).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The six seeded teams for the 1990 tournament were announced on 7 December 1989, two days ahead of the draw.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The FIFA Organising Committee also decided ahead of the draw, to allocate the six seeded teams into the first position of the six groups, in the alphabetic order of their seeding rank: first seed to Group A, second seed to Group B, etc.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The seeds were decided by FIFA, primarily based on the nations' ranked position in the 1986 World Cup (counting double), with the ranked position in the 1982 World Cup also considered as a secondary influence (counting normal).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Six of the final eight in 1986 had qualified for the 1990 tournament, the missing nations being Mexico (quarter-final in 1986) and France (third place).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy did not reach the final eight in 1986, but despite this were still seeded first in 1990 as hosts.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In total, the primary seeding criteria hereby resulted in seven countries to be potentially seeded.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As the tournament structure only had place for the selection of six seeded teams, this left FIFA needing to exclude one of the six teams qualifying for a seed based on the primary sporting criteria.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA first decided, that all qualified teams having played the 1986 semi-finals (Argentina, Germany, Belgium), should be guaranteed a seeding place behind the first seeded host nation Italy.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Consequently, one of the three qualified nations who were eliminated in the 1986 quarter-finals (Brazil, England or Spain), should not be seeded based on the secondary sporting criteria - looking at their 1982 FIFA World Cup results.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Owing to their performance in 1982, but also to their overall World Cup record, Brazil were seeded third, and not considered to drop out of the seedings.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA therefore had to choose if England or Spain should be granted the last seeding slot, and ultimately opted to seed England ahead of Spain.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain had only been eliminated in their 1986 quarter-final on penalties, albeit by fourth-placed Belgium, while England had been defeated in their 1986 quarter-final after 90 minutes by eventual winners Argentina.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If the only criteria had been the 1986 ranking, then Spain should have been seeded as #6 instead of England; a viewpoint being supported by FIFA President João Havelange as late as 29 November 1989.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If taking the 1982 ranking into consideration, England however had performed slightly better than Spain - as they had finished ahead of them in Group B of the second group stage.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If only considering the results of the 1978 event, it could on the other hand have been counter argued, that Spain by their group stage performance and Netherlands by their silver medal accomplishment, should have been seeded rather than England and Belgium who both had failed to qualify.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spanish officials believed the seeding was contrived to ensure England would be placed in Group F, the group to be held off the Italian mainland, in a bid to contain England's hooliganism problems.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their coach Luis Suárez said, "We feel we've been cheated...they wanted to seed England and to send it to Cagliari at all costs.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA countered that "the formula was based on the teams' respective showings during the previous two World Cups.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This is in no way a concession to English hooliganism".
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, this argument was countered by the fact that Netherlands had themselves failed to qualify for both the 1982 and 1986 World Cups, which was considered the most important factor in the decision not to seed them.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the group stage had been completed, England could be said to have justified their seeded position by winning their Group F ahead of Ireland and Netherlands; while Spain seemed to have made their own point about being worth a seeded position, by defeating Belgium to top their own Group E.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 9 December 1989, the draw was conducted at the Palazzo dello Sport in Rome, where the teams were drawn out from the three pots to be placed with the seeded teams in their predetermined groups, in alphabetic order.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A special draw decided teams should first be drawn from Pot 1, then from Pot 3, and finally from Pot 2.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each drawn team also had their group position number drawn from a separate group bowl, in order to decide their exact match schedule.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The only stipulation of the draw was that no group could feature two South American teams.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The procedure for the draw, was presented by FIFA at a press meeting the day before the draw.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, after having received objections from Italian officials, FIFA opted to slightly change their special Pot 2 rule, during the last 24 hours ahead of the draw.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] When FIFA accepted to change the Pot 2 rule into the final version presented at the televised draw, this lowered the chance for the Italian Group A to draw a South American Pot 2 team, from the 80% chance created by the initial wording to only a 33% chance (two out of six teams).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ceremony was hosted by Italian television presenter Pippo Baudo, with Italian actress Sophia Loren and opera singer Luciano Pavarotti conducting the draw alongside FIFA general secretary Sepp Blatter.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The event also featured the official mascot of this World Cup, *Ciao*, a stick figure player with a football head and an Italian tricolour body that formed the word "ITALIA" when deconstructed and reconstructed.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In each group, the teams would play three matches, one against each of the other teams.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Victories would be granted 2 points, while a draw awarded 1 point.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After completion of the group stage, the best two teams of each group as well as the four best ranked third places, advanced to round 16 in the knockout stage.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This format was identical with the tournament structure being used in 1986.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A total of 52 games would be played, including the final and a match for third place between the two semi-final losers.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament generated a record low goals-per-game average and a then-record of 16 red cards were handed out.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the knockout stage, many teams played defensively for 120 minutes, with the intention of trying their luck in the penalty shoot-out, rather than risk going forward.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two exceptions were the eventual champions West Germany and hosts Italy, the only teams to win three of their four knockout matches in normal time.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were four penalty shoot-outs, a record equalled with the 2006, 2014, and 2018 tournaments, until it was surpassed by the 2022 tournament, with five.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Eight matches went to extra time, also a record tied with the 2014 tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Losing finalists Argentina were prime examples of this trend of cautious defensive play, choosing to do so because 3 of their best players were left off the squad due to injury.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They scored only five goals in the entire tournament (a record low for a finalist).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina also became the first team to advance twice on penalty shoot-outs and the first team to fail to score and have a player sent off in a World Cup final.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Largely as a result of this trend IFAB introduced the back-pass rule in time for the 1994 tournament to make it harder for teams to time-waste by repeatedly passing the ball back for their goalkeepers to pick up.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three, rather than two points would be awarded for victories at future tournaments to help further encourage attacking play.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon reached the quarter-finals, where they were narrowly defeated by England.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They opened the tournament with a shock victory over reigning champions Argentina, before topping the group ahead of them, Romania and European Championship runners-up the Soviet Union.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their success was fired by the goals of Roger Milla, a 38-year-old forward who came out of international retirement to join the national squad at the last moment after a personal request from Cameroonian President Paul Biya.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Milla's four goals and flamboyant goal celebrations made him one of the tournament's biggest stars as well as taking Cameroon to the last eight.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Most of Cameroon's squad was made up of players who played in France's premier football league, Ligue 1 - French is one of the officially spoken languages in Cameroon, it being a former French territory.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In reaching this stage, they had gone further than any African nation had managed in a World Cup before; a feat not surpassed until Morocco reached the semi-final in 2022.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon's feat (equalled by Senegal in 2002 and Ghana in 2010) remains the best by a Sub-Saharan African team.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their success was African football's biggest yet on the world stage and FIFA subsequently decided to allocate the CAF qualifying zone an additional place for the next World Cup tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite the performances of nations such as Cameroon, Colombia, Ireland, Romania and Costa Rica, the semi-finalists consisted of Argentina, England, Italy and West Germany, all previous World Cup winners, with eight previous titles between them.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the 1970 tournament, this is only the second time in the history of the World Cup this has occurred.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams which finished first, second and third had also contested both the two previous World Cup Finals between themselves.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Group stage saw the twenty-four teams divided into six groups of four teams.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each group was a round-robin of six games, in which each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams were awarded two points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams coming first and second in each group qualified for the Round of 16.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The four best third-placed teams would also advance to the next stage.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As was typical of a World Cup staged in Europe, the matches all started at either 5:00 or 9:00 in the evening; this allowed for the games to avoid being played in the heat of an Italian summer, which would soar past 86F (30C) all over Italy.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hosts Italy won Group A with a 100 percent record.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat Austria 1–0 thanks to substitute Salvatore 'Totò' Schillaci, who had played only one international before but would become a star during the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A second 1–0 victory followed against a United States team already thumped 5–1 by Czechoslovakia.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Czechoslovaks ended runners-up in the group, while the USA's first appearance in a World Cup Finals since 1950 ended with three consecutive defeats.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon defeated world champions Argentina 1–0.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite ending the match with only nine men, the African team held on for a shock 1–0 win, with contrasting fortunes for the Biyik brothers: François Omam-Biyik scoring the winning goal with a downward header, shortly after seeing André Kana-Biyik sent off for a serious foul.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon's second red card was awarded to Benjamin Massing for up-ending Caniggia in the last few minutes as Argentina pressed for an equalizer.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Cameroon's second game, the introduction of Roger Milla was the catalyst for a 2–1 win over Romania, Milla scoring twice from the bench (making him the oldest goalscorer in the tournament).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] With progression assured, Cameroon slumped to a 4–0 defeat in their final group game to the Soviet Union (in what would be their last World Cup due to the dissolution of the Soviet Union), who were striving to stay in the tournament on goal difference after successive 2–0 defeats.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina lost their veteran goalkeeper, Nery Pumpido, to a broken leg during their victory over the USSR: his replacement, Sergio Goycochea, proved to be one of the stars of their tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final match, a 1–1 draw between Romania and Argentina sent both through, equal on points and on goal difference but with Romania having the advantage on goals scored; Romania were thus second, and Argentina qualified as one of the best third-placed teams.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Costa Rica beat Scotland 1–0 in their first match, lost 1–0 to Brazil in their second, then saw off Sweden 2–1 to claim a place in the second round.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil took maximum points from the group.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They began with a 2–1 win over Sweden, then beat both Costa Rica and Scotland 1–0.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Scotland's 2–1 win over Sweden was not enough to save them from an early return home as one of the two lowest-ranked third-placed teams.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group D featured the most goals of all the groups, most due to two large wins of West Germany and defensive inadequacies of a United Arab Emirates team that lost 2–0 to Colombia, 5–1 to West Germany and 4–1 to Yugoslavia.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The West Germans topped the group after a 4–1 opening victory over group runners-up Yugoslavia.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winners of Group E were Spain, for whom Míchel hit a hat-trick as they beat South Korea 3–1 in an unbeaten group campaign.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Belgium won their first two games against South Korea and Uruguay to ensure their progress; Uruguay's advance to the second round came with an injury-time winner against South Korea to edge them through as the weakest of the third-placed sides to remain in the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group F featured the Netherlands, England, the Republic of Ireland and Egypt.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the six group games, no team managed to score more than once in a match.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England beat Egypt 1–0—the only match with a decisive result—and that was enough to win the group.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England took the lead with an early goal for Lineker against Ireland, but Sheedy's late equaliser secured a draw.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Netherlands drew with Egypt: they had taken a 1–0 lead, but Egypt equalised with a penalty by Abdelghani.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England then drew 0–0 with the Netherlands; a goal from a free-kick by Pearce was disallowed.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] For the second World Cup in succession, however, England lost their captain Bryan Robson to an injury which put him out of the tournament, just over halfway through their second match.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Ireland missed a number of scoring opportunities in the second half of the other 0–0 draw against Egypt.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the first four matches all four teams had equal records with two draws, one goal for and one goal against.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Both teams qualified, but they had to draw lots to place the teams in second and third place.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored; 4) Drawing of lots (if deciding qualification).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The knockout stage involved the 16 teams that qualified from the group stage of the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were four rounds of matches, with each round eliminating half of the teams entering that round.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The successive rounds were: round of 16, quarter-finals, semi-finals and the final.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Scores after extra time are indicated by (a.e.t.) and penalty shoot-outs are indicated by (pen.).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Two of the ties—Brazil vs Argentina and Italy vs Uruguay—pitted former champion countries against each other and West Germany met the Netherlands in a rematch of the 1974 World Cup Final.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The all-South American game was won for Argentina by a goal from Claudio Caniggia with 10 minutes remaining after a run through the Brazilian defence by Diego Maradona and a strong performance from their goalkeeper Sergio Goycochea.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It would later come to light that Branco had been offered water spiked with tranquillisers by Maradona and Ricardo Giusti during half time, to slow him down in the second half.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Initially discredited by the press, Branco would be publicly proven right years later, when Maradona confessed the episode on a TV show in Argentina.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Hosts Italy beat Uruguay 2–0, thanks to goals from Schillaci and Aldo Serena.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match between West Germany and the Netherlands was held in Milan, and both sides featured players from the two Milanese clubs (Germans Andreas Brehme, Lothar Matthäus and Jürgen Klinsmann for Internazionale, and Dutchmen Marco van Basten, Ruud Gullit and Frank Rijkaard for Milan).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] After 22 minutes Rudi Völler and Rijkaard were both dismissed after a number of incidents between the two players, including Rijkaard spitting on Völler.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] As the players walked off the pitch together, Rijkaard spat on Völler a second time.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Early in the second half, Jürgen Klinsmann put the West Germans ahead and Andreas Brehme added a second with eight minutes left.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A Ronald Koeman penalty for the Netherlands in the 89th minute narrowed the score to 2–1 but the Germans saw the game out to gain some revenge for their exit to the Dutch in the previous European Championship.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Colombia, Roger Milla was introduced as a second-half substitute with the game goalless, eventually breaking the deadlock midway in extra time.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Three minutes later he netted a second after Colombian goalkeeper, René Higuita was dispossessed by Milla while well out of his goal, leaving the striker free to slot the ball into the empty net.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Though the deficit was soon reduced to 2–1, Cameroon held on to become the first African team to reach the World Cup quarter-finals.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Costa Rica were beaten 4–1 by Czechoslovakia, for whom Tomáš Skuhravý scored the tournament's second and final hat-trick.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Republic of Ireland's match with Romania remained goalless after extra time and the Irish side won 5–4 on penalties.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] David O'Leary converted the penalty that clinched Ireland's place in the quarter-finals.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Ireland thus became the first team since Sweden in 1938 to reach the last eight in a World Cup finals tournament without winning a match outright.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Yugoslavia beat Spain 2–1 after extra time, with Dragan Stojković scoring both the Yugoslavs' goals.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England were the final qualifier against Belgium, as midfielder David Platt's swivelling volley broke the stalemate with the game moments away from a penalty shoot-out.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The first game of the last 8 saw Argentina and a Yugoslav side, reduced to 10 men after only half an hour, play out a goalless stalemate.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The holders reached the semi-finals after winning the penalty shoot-out 3–2, despite Maradona having his penalty saved.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A second Argentine miss (by Pedro Troglio) looked to have eliminated them until goalkeeper Sergio Goycochea – playing because first choice Nery Pumpido broke his leg during the group stage – rescued his side by stopping the Yugoslavs' final two spotkicks.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Republic of Ireland's World Cup run was brought to an end by a single goal from Schillaci in the first half of their quarter-final with hosts Italy, thus becoming the team who advanced the furthest in a World Cup without winning a single match.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] West Germany beat Czechoslovakia with a 25th minute Lothar Matthäus penalty.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The quarter-final between England and Cameroon was the only quarter-final to produce more than one goal.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Despite Cameroon's heroics earlier in the tournament, David Platt put England ahead in the 25th minute.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the second half, the game was turned on its head during a five-minute stretch: first Cameroon were awarded a penalty from which Emmanuel Kunde scored the equaliser; then in the 65th minute Eugene Ekeke put Cameroon ahead.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Cameroon came within eight minutes of reaching the semi-finals before they conceded a penalty, which Gary Lineker converted.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Midway through extra time, England were awarded another penalty and Lineker again scored from the spot.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England were through to the semi-finals for the first time since 1966.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The first semi-final featured the host nation, Italy, and the world champions, Argentina in Naples.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] 'Toto' Schillaci scored yet again to put Italy ahead in the 17th minute, but Claudio Caniggia equalised midway through the second half, breaking Walter Zenga's clean sheet streak throughout the tournament.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were no more goals in the 90 minutes or in extra time despite Maradona (who played for Naples in Serie A at the time) showing glimpses of magic, but there was a sending-off: Ricardo Giusti of Argentina was shown the red card in the 13th minute of extra time.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentina went through on penalties, winning the shoot-out 4–3 after more heroics from Goycochea.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The semi-final between West Germany and England at Juventus' home stadium in Turin was goalless at half-time.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Then, in the 60th minute, a free-kick tapped to Andreas Brehme resulted in a shot which was deflected off Paul Parker into his own net.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England equalised with ten minutes left; Gary Lineker was the scorer, Parker somewhat redeeming himself by providing the assist.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Klinsmann was guilty of two glaring misses and both sides struck a post.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England had another Platt goal disallowed for offside.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match went to penalties, and West Germany went on to win the shoot-out 4–3, Pearce having his penalty saved and Waddle firing over the bar.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The two matches had the exact same score at 1–1, an identical penalty shootout score at 4–3, and the same order of penalties scored.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The game saw three goals in a 15-minute spell near the end of the match.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Roberto Baggio opened the scoring after a mistake by England's goalkeeper Peter Shilton, in his final game before international retirement, presented a simple opportunity.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A header by David Platt levelled the game 10 minutes later but Schillaci was fouled in the penalty area five minutes later, leading to a penalty.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Schillaci himself got up to convert the kick to win him the tournament's Golden Boot for his six-goal tally.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Nicola Berti had a goal ruled out minutes later, but the hosts claimed third place.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England had the consolation prize of the Fair Play award, having received no red cards and the lowest average number of yellows per match.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The final between West Germany and Argentina has been cited as one of two most cynical and lowest-quality of all World Cup Finals, next to the 2010, between Spain and Netherlands.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the 65th minute, Argentina's Pedro Monzon – himself only recently on as a substitute – was sent off for a foul on Jürgen Klinsmann.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Monzon was the first player sent off in a World Cup Final.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentina, weakened by suspension and injury, offered little attacking threat throughout a contest dominated by the West Germans, who struggled to create many clear goalscoring opportunities.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The only goal of the contest arrived in the 85th minute when Mexican referee Edgardo Codesal awarded a penalty to West Germany, after a foul on Rudi Völler by Roberto Sensini leading to Argentinian protests.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] An earlier possible foul by Goycoecha, who tripped Klaus Augenthaler in the box, had not been given.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] German commentators speculated, that the subsequent penalty was therefore a concession by the referee.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Andreas Brehme converted the spot kick to settle the contest.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the closing moments, Argentina were reduced to nine after Gustavo Dezotti, who had already been given a yellow card earlier in the match, received a red card when he hauled Jürgen Kohler to the ground during a stoppage in play.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The 1–0 scoreline provided another first: Argentina were the first team to fail to score in a World Cup Final.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] With its third title (and three second-place finishes) West Germany – in its final tournament before national reunification – became the most successful World Cup nation at the time along with Italy and Brazil (who had also won three titles each then).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] West German manager Franz Beckenbauer became the first man to both captain (in 1974) and manage a World Cup winning team, and only the second man (after Mário Zagallo of Brazil) to win the World Cup as a player and as team manager.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was also the first time a team from UEFA won the final against a non-European team.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Salvatore Schillaci received the Golden Boot award for scoring six goals in the World Cup.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] This made him the second Italian footballer to have this honour, after Paolo Rossi won the award in 1982.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In total, 115 goals were scored by 75 players (none credited as own goals).
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA published the first All-Star Team in 1938, but it never made an All-Star Team again until 1990 due to ensuing complaints.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In 1990 an All-Star Team was announced in combination with the Golden Ball ceremony.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was chosen by the same journalists who chose the best player, but this team is still considered unofficial.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] After the tournament, FIFA published a ranking of all teams that competed in the 1990 World Cup finals based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The sponsors of the 1990 FIFA World Cup are divided into two categories: FIFA World Cup Sponsors and Italy Supporters.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot of this World Cup was "Ciao", a stick figure player with a football head and an Italian tricolore body.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official match ball of this World Cup was the "Etrusco Unico", manufactured by Adidas.
[src:sicily/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official song of this World Cup was "Un'estate italiana".
[src:sicily/2003-world-championships-in-athletics] Note: * Indicates athletes who ran in preliminary rounds.
[src:sicily/2003-world-championships-in-athletics] 1 Jerome Young of the United States originally finished first in 44.50, but was disqualified after he tested positive for drugs in 2004.
[src:sicily/2003-world-championships-in-athletics] 2 The United States (Calvin Harrison, Tyree Washington, Derrick Brew, Jerome Young) originally finished first in 2:58.88, but were disqualified after Jerome Young and Calvin Harrison both tested positive for drugs in 2004.
[src:sicily/2003-world-championships-in-athletics] Note: * Indicates medalists who ran in preliminary rounds.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The origins of the team go back to 1900, when **Messina F.C.** was founded in the city.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The club has spent most of its existence in the lower Italian football leagues.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] They last competed in Serie B in 2007–08, which followed three consecutive seasons in Serie A.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In July 2008, Messina were excluded from professional football due to financial issues, being later registered into amateur Serie D.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The farthest Messina has reached in the Coppa Italia is the last 16.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In the past, they have also reached the semi-finals in the Coppa Italia Serie C.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Messina have appeared in the Italy's top league, Serie A, for a total of five seasons.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The club's first spell in the league was in the 1960s; the second began in the 2000s decade.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Messina Football Club were officially founded on 1 December 1900 by Marangolo with the help of Anglican reverend "Caulifield".
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] At the college where Marangolo visited he had also made the acquaintance of Ignazio Majo Pagano who formed Anglo Palermitan (Palermo) on his return, only a month before Messina.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The first Sicilian derby was held between Messina and Palermo on 18 April 1901; 1,000 fans turned out to Via Notarbartolo for the match.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The game ended 3–2 to the Palermitan side.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The earthquake of 1908, which killed 60,000 people in Messina, later affected the club in a large manner; deaths included Charles Bousfield Huleatt, players Frank John Carter, Walter Oates and financial backer George H.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Football resumed in Messina the following year, thanks largely to Arthur Barret Lascelles who used his own money to ensure football activity in the city would continue.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] By 1910, the funds of Barret had dried up, and the club was folded, **Società Ginnastica Garibaldi Messina** (*Gymnastic Society Garibaldi Messina*) briefly took its place, until it too was dissolved due to the First World War.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The club participated in the Italian Football Championship of 1921–22, organised by the C.C.I., finishing third in the Sicilian group section; this was the first championship in which clubs from the island were entered.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The following season the FIGC and CCI were unified.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] This coincided with mergers in Messina, as another side, **Umberto I Messina**, was incorporated into US Messinese, and, therefore, the club changed its name to **US Messinese Umberto I** in October 1922.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The following month this new side was fused again, this time with Messina Sporting Club; creating the **Messina Football Club**.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Only two years later, in December 1924, FC Messina was melted, and the players became part of the reformed **US Messinese**.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In March 2009, Rome-based entrepreneur Alfredo Di Lullo acquired **Football Club Messina Peloro** in a blind auction held by the Court of Messina in April 2009.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Rinascita Messina** (*rinascita* means "revived").
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Since the summer of 2014, the new name of the club is **Associazioni Calcio Riunite Messina**.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In the 2014–15 season, the club was relegated to Serie D, but it was readmitted to Lega Pro for involvement in sporting fraud.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Since the summer of 2015, the new owner and president is Natale Stracuzzi.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The club failed to submit its surety by the 5 July 2017 deadline and was expelled by Lega Pro.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Messina S.s.d. a r.l.** was admitted to the 2017–18 Serie D.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In 1973, the first ultras firm of ACR Messina was founded: the "Fedelissimi".
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In 1980, "Gioventù Giallorossa" was born, revolutionizing the supporter scene in Sicily and opening sections in Rome, Milan, and Turin.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In 1983, some small firms merged into a single group called "NOCS".
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] During the club's time in Serie A and Serie B, it had thousands of non-organized fans, a number that has significantly declined over the last twenty years.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Messina's fanbase has reached peaks of 38,000 spectators at home and 10,000 away.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The former club **Football Club Messina Peloro** have played their home matches in the new Stadio Comunale San Filippo since the 2004–05 to 2008–09 season.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Since the season 2009–10 plays here the current team of **A.C.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The capacity of the stadium is 37,895 seats.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] It is named after the part of the city in which it is located, but a couple of petitions aim to rename it after the former Messina manager Franco Scoglio or the Messina Saint Hannibal Mary Di Francia.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] The old stadium, the 11,000 seater Stadio Comunale Giovanni Celeste, is now used by **S.S.D.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] Città di Messina**, the second team of the city.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] For the 2022–23 season, Coop – Gruppo Radenza served as ACR Messina's main shirt sponsor.
[src:sicily/a-c-r-messina] In October 2023, StarCasinò Sport became the club's main shirt sponsor under a two-season agreement covering the 2023–24 and 2024–25 seasons.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo borders the region of Marche to the north, Lazio to the west and northwest, Molise to the south, and the Adriatic Sea to the east.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Geographically, Abruzzo is divided into a mountainous area in the west, which includes the highest massifs of the Apennines, such as the Gran Sasso d'Italia and the Maiella, and a coastal area in the east, with beaches on the Adriatic Sea.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Culturally, Abruzzo is considered a region of Southern Italy; however, geographically it is often considered part of Central Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Because of its historic association with the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies, the Italian statistical authority ISTAT deems it to be part of Southern Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo is known as "*the greenest region in Europe*" as half of the region's territory is protected through national parks and nature reserves, more than any other region in Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There are three national parks, one regional park, and 38 protected nature reserves.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] These ensure the survival of rare species, such as the golden eagle, the Abruzzo (or Abruzzese) chamois, the Apennine wolf, and the Marsican brown bear.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo's parks and reserves host 75% of Europe's animal species.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The region is also home to Calderone, one of Europe's southernmost glaciers.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Nineteenth-century Italian diplomat and journalist Primo Levi (1853–1917) chose the adjectives *forte e gentile* ("strong and kind") to capture what he saw as the character of the region and its people.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] *Forte e gentile* has since become the motto of the region.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] According to other hypotheses, the name could also derive from *abruptus* (Latin for "steep" or "precipitous").
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Although an earlier presence cannot be ruled out, findings in the region related to archaic humans date from around 700,000 years ago (Acheulean Culture).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Thousands of flint tools and weapons have been collected on fluvial terraces (e.g.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Madonna del Freddo at Chieti) and near former lakes (e.g.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Valle Giumentina at Caramanico Terme and Valle Peligna at Popoli).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] These testify to the presence of different *Homo* species over time, ranging from *Homo erectus* and Neanderthals to modern humans.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] A site located at Popoli (Svolte di Popoli) also contained hippopotamus bones.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The most important evidence of Neanderthals' presence in the region was found in caves in Calascio and dates back to the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Significant evidence of Upper Paleolithic human populations has been found in various places, including the Fucino depression and Montebello di Bertona, the latter giving its name to a distinctive stoneworking technique called "Bertonian".
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After the Mesolithic transition, which was characterized by climate change and a lack of food resources, agriculture was introduced in Abruzzo by Neolithic farmers from the Middle East.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] A skeleton from Lama dei Peligni in the province of Chieti was dated back to 6,540 BC using radiometric dating.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In Abruzzo and Marche, villages typical of the Ripoli culture in the 5–6th millennium BC consisted of huts, and were generally located on fluvial terraces or hills overlooking rivers.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In some cases, they were defended by a moat.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] These people practiced agriculture, husbandry, hunting, fishing, and production of pottery, which was painted or decorated.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Other older Neolithic cultures present in Abruzzo are called the Impressed Ceramic culture and the Catignano culture.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Bronze Age saw the spread of the Apennine culture and the Subapennine culture in central-southern Italy, including in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The former has been associated with pastoralism, and the latter with agriculture.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] During the Late Bronze Age, the Proto-Villanovan culture emerged in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There are sites of Iron Age necropoli at Fiorano (Loreto Aprutino's *frazione*), Campovalano (Campli), Alfedena, and Capestrano.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] At the end of the Iron Age, Abruzzo was inhabited by different tribes, including the peoples defined by ancient Roman tradition as Sabelli: Oscan-speaking Pentri, Carricini, and Frentani, and, more generically, the Osco-Umbrian Aequi, Praetutii, Vestini, Marrucini, Marsi, and Paeligni.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Considered strong warriors by ancient writers, the tribes fought against the Romans in the Samnite Wars (from 343 to 290 BC).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Some tribes accepted the alliance with the Romans, while others surrendered after the Samnite Wars.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Following progressive Romanization, they supported the Romans and contributed to many victories in the 3rd and 2nd centuries BC.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] They fought again with Rome during the Social War (91–87 BC) to gain political rights and created the ephemeral state called Italia with Corfinio as the capital.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After the Social War, they obtained Roman citizenship and in the Imperial period favoured economic activities such as trade and pastoralism.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] On the basis of a division by Augustus, the territory of what is now Abruzzo was part of "Regio V Picenum" and especially "Regio IV Sabina et Samnium".
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Much later, the region corresponded to the Valeria province, according to the Diocletian decisions, and was among the first to see the arrival of Christianity.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Evidence from archeological sites shows that many cities in Abruzzo date back to ancient times.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Corfinio was known as Corfinium when it was the chief city of the Paeligni, and it became the capital of "Italia" against the Romans during the Social War.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Today's Chieti has been inhabited since the Chalcolithic era, and was an important center for the Marrucini (Teate Marrucinorum).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Atri was known as Hatria and Teramo was known variously in ancient times as Interamnia and Teramne.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Pinna (today Penne), Anxanum (Lanciano), Hortona (Ortona), Histonium (Vasto), Sulmona, and Marruvium (San Benedetto dei Marsi) are among the settlements that are still inhabited while others are no longer so, such as Cluviae near Casoli.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire and the Gothic War between the Byzantine Empire and the Ostrogothic Kingdom, looting and devastation of monasteries and towns accompanied the arrival of Germanic Lombards in the region.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Around 572, the Lombards divided Abruzzo into the Duchy of Benevento and that of Spoleto, with the Faroald I of Spoleto becoming the first Duke of Spoleto.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] His successor, Ariulf of Spoleto, annexed other territories: the former territories controlled by the Aequi, Marsi, Peligni, and Vestini.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the 8th century, Transamund II of Spoleto rebelled against Liutprand, King of the Lombards, but was able to recover his duchy and also to include other remaining territories of the former Valeria province.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After the beginning of domination by the Franks, in 801, Teate (today's Chieti) also passed from the Lombardic Duchy of Benevento to the Frankish Duchy of Spoleto.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 843, some territories were separated from the duchy (all the region together with the district of Rieti, except that of Teramo, according to *Liber provincialis*), with Celano as the capital.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Counts of Marsi from different lineages ruled "Marsia" from 843 to 926.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 871, Louis II of Italy founded, as the Carolingian Emperor, a monastery, which would become very powerful in the history of Abruzzo (Abbey of San Clemente a Casauria).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] With the rule of Hugh of Italy from 926, the territories were divided: Penne and Teate to Atto I, and today's province of L'Aquila to Berardo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After two attempted conquests by two Norman princes of Capua in Abruzzo, two other Normans, Robert Guiscard and Robert I of Loritello, conquered Teate, Valva, and Penne.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Later, all of Abruzzo was definitively conquered by Norman Roger II of Sicily.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1156, his son, William I of Sicily, had these victories officially recognized by Pope Adrian IV.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] As part of the Kingdom of Sicily, Abruzzo was involved in the conflicts following the death of William II of Sicily in 1189.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The territories sided with Constance, Queen of Sicily and Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor, but after the death of the former in 1198, they were invaded by Otto IV, Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] They were also involved in the conflicts between Frederick II (son of Queen Constance) and Pope Gregory IX, including the War of the Keys.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Following this, the administrative region of Abruzzo was formed in the 1230s, when Frederick II divided his realms into justiciarates, with Abruzzo forming one of them.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The newly founded L'Aquila was destroyed by Manfred, King of Sicily (son of Frederick II) in 1259, and in the Battle of Tagliacozzo (1268), supported the defeat of his nephew Conradin against Charles I of Anjou, the new king of Sicily.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] From the last half of the 13th century, L'Aquila took a central role in the region.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo was divided into *Abruzzo Citra* (nearer Abruzzo) and *Abruzzo Ultra* (further Abruzzo) by Charles I of Anjou in the 1270s.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1302, after the rebellion called Sicilian Vespers and the subsequent war, the Peace of Caltabellotta divided the former Kingdom of Sicily as follows: Sicily to the Crown of Aragon and the Southern Italian Peninsula (including Abruzzo) still to the Capetian House of Anjou.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The region was profoundly affected during the wars that followed a conspiracy which resulted in the assassination of Andrew, Duke of Calabria, the husband of Queen Joanna I of Naples.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Different towns (L'Aquila, Penne, Chieti, Lanciano, Ortona) sided at first with the brother of the victim, Louis I of Hungary.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1443, Alfonso V of Aragon, King of Sicily, conquered the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the decades that followed, Abruzzo saw many battles, including the ones associated with the War of L'Aquila.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Under the Aragonese rulers, L'Aquila started to become a military center, giving up its political and economic importance to Chieti.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] This period was characterized by economic decline and the spread of brigandage, but coastal centers benefited from trade with the Republic of Venice's overseas territories.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Shortly after the Italian War of 1494–1495 carried out by Charles VIII of France, the Kingdom of Naples returned to Ferdinand II of Aragon.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In this and in the following conflict between the Kingdom of France and the Kingdom of Spain over the Kingdom of Naples, Abruzzo sided with France, but Spain won in 1503 and started to dominate the Kingdom of Naples with its viceroys.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In Abruzzo, the aristocracy tried to regain more control when there was a rebellion in the Kingdom of Naples led by a fisherman named Masaniello in 1647.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] At the beginning of the 18th century, the region was affected by destructive earthquakes, which also devastated L'Aquila (1703 Apennine earthquakes) and Sulmona (1706 Abruzzo earthquake), and the War of the Spanish Succession, with the Austrian siege at Pescara in 1707.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1734, Charles III of the House of Bourbon, King of Spain, ended the short Habsburg Austrian domination, which contributed to large land concentrations in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In accordance with a general diffidence against the Enlightenment ideas, the Abruzzo population of different social classes rebelled in an improvised way against French invasion in 1798 and 1799.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After the proclamation of the ephemeral Parthenopean Republic, they continued to be hostile to French invaders (*Sanfedismo*).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] During the client kingdom (1806–1815) of Napoleon, in 1806, Abruzzo Ultra was divided into two, as Abruzzo Ultra I and Abruzzo Ultra II, divided at the Gran Sasso d'Italia; the same Citra/Ultra I/Ultra II scheme was used for Calabria.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The return of the Bourbons was granted by the Congress of Vienna, while Abruzzo was plagued by decline and brigandage.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The House of Bourbon-Two Sicilies established the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies in 1816, and ruled until Italian unification (also known as the *Risorgimento*).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Rebellions also sprang up in 1821, 1841 and 1848 with a variety of causes, including liberal, Jacobin, or reactionary ideas.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] During the unification of Italy, in 1860, Abruzzo became part of the Kingdom of Sardinia and, in 1861, the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Some supporters of the Bourbons fought against volunteers of Garibaldi, and later banded together with common criminals to participate for political reasons in brigandage, which would be eradicated years later.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] However, many accepted the new order with neither enthusiasm nor opposition.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Since 1870, due to its economic conditions, Abruzzo saw massive emigration to other regions and countries, which contributed to the Italian diaspora.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] During the Italian fascism period, Pescara became an important center for its homonymous port, tourism, and trade.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] With the Second World War, Abruzzo was on the Gustav Line, part of the German Winter Line.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] One of the most brutal battles was the Battle of Ortona.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo was the location of two prisoner-of-war camps, Campo 21 in Chieti, and Campo 78 in Sulmona.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Sulmona camp had also served as a POW camp in World War I; much of the facility is still intact and attracts tourists.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Despite the high level of destruction and victims caused by the Second World War, there was remarkable development in the second half of the 20th century, which particularly favored the Fucino and Adriatic coastal areas.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Indeed, starting from 1964, Abruzzo started to be affected by a late economic miracle, with a historical increase in consumption and investment.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There was rapid industrialisation of different areas of the region, especially Val Vibrata in the Province of Teramo, and Val Pescara and Val di Sangro, both located in the Province of Chieti.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] By 1981, Abruzzo had a higher level of industrialization than some Central-Northern regions and was in evident contrast with other Southern regions.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the 1960s, L'Aquila established the University of L'Aquila, whereas Chieti, Pescara and Teramo founded the Gabriele d'Annunzio University, which became a state-funded university in 1982.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1993, the University of Teramo was split from the Gabriele d'Annunzio University.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Owing to geographic rivalry between L'Aquila located in the mountainous area, and Pescara and Chieti located in the Adriatic area, the decision was made in 1966 to construct two parallel east-west motorways: Autostrada A24 and Autostrada A25.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In particular, the Autostrada A24 resulted in the expensive construction of the Gran Sasso tunnel, which also hosts the Laboratori Nazionali del Gran Sasso, a prominent underground particle physics research center.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the 1948 Italian Constitution, Abruzzo was unified with Molise into the Abruzzi e Molise region, though in the first draft, Abruzzo and Molise were separate.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1963, Abruzzi e Molise was separated into the two regions of Abruzzo and Molise.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The decision concerning the location of regional headquarters was influenced by the rivalry between L'Aquila and Pescara, which was in turn affected by the rivalry between Lorenzo Natali's and Remo Gaspari's factions inside the Christian Democracy majority party.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the 1970s, this caused street protests and riots in both cities and the decision to place some headquarters in Pescara outside the capital L'Aquila.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The province of Teramo and province of Pescara now comprise the territory of the former Abruzzo Ulteriore I.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo Ulteriore II is now the province of L'Aquila.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo Citeriore is now the province of Chieti.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Geographically, Abruzzo is located in a roughly central position on the Italian Peninsula, stretching from the heart of the Apennines to the Adriatic Sea, and is characterized by mainly mountainous and wild land.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The mountainous area features a vast plateau, with Gran Sasso, which, at 2,912 metres (9,554 ft), is the highest peak of the Apennines, and Mount Majella at 2,793 metres (9,163 ft).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Adriatic coastline is characterized by long sandy beaches to the north and pebbly beaches to the south.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo is known for its landscapes and natural environment, parks and nature reserves, and characteristic hillside areas rich in vineyards and olive groves.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Many beaches have been awarded the Blue Flag beach status.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There are two climatic zones in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The coastal strip and sub-Apennine hills have a climate distinct from that of the mountainous interior.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Coastal areas have a Mediterranean climate with hot dry summers and mild winters.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Inland hilly areas have a sublittoral climate with temperatures decreasing with altitude.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Precipitation is also strongly affected by the presence of the Apennines mountain range.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Rainfall is abundant on slopes oriented to the west, and lower in the east and on east-facing slopes.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Adriatic coast is shielded from rainfall by the barrier effect created by the Apennines.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The minimum annual rainfall is found in some inland valleys sheltered by mountain ranges, such as the Peligna or Tirino valleys (near Ofena, Capestrano), annual rainfall as low as 500 millimetres (19.7 inches) has been recorded.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Rainfall along the coast almost never falls below 600 millimetres (23.6 inches).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Pescara has relatively less rainfall (about 700 millimetres (27.6 inches)) than Chieti (about 1,000 millimetres (39.4 inches)).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The highest rainfall occurs in upland areas on the border with Lazio; these areas are especially vulnerable to Atlantic disturbances.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Around 1,500 to 2,000 millimetres (59 to 79 inches) of precipitation is typical.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The flora of Abruzzo is typically Mediterranean.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Along the coastal belt, Mediterranean shrubland is the dominant natural vegetation, with species including myrtle, heather, and mastic.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Inland, there are olive, pine, willow, oak, poplar, alder, arbutus, broom, acacia, capers, rosemary, hawthorn, licorice, and almond trees, interspersed with oak trees.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] At elevations between 600 and 1,000 metres (2,000 and 3,300 ft), there is sub-montane vegetation, with mixed woodlands of oak and turkey oak, maple, and hornbeam; shrubs include dog rose and red juniper.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Elevations between 1,000 and 1,900 metres (3,300 and 6,200 ft) are dominated by beech.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the Apennine Mountains, at elevations above 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), species include alpine orchid, mountain juniper, silver fir, black cranberry, and the Abruzzo edelweiss.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The fauna of Abruzzo is very diverse, including the region's symbol, the Abruzzo chamois (*Rupicapra pyrenaica ornata*), which has recovered from near-extinction.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Common species include the Marsican brown bear, Italian wolf, red deer, lynx, roe deer, snow vole, fox, porcupine, wild cat, wild boar, badger, otter, and viper.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The natural parks of the region are the Abruzzo National Park, the Gran Sasso and Monti della Laga National Park, the Maiella National Park, and the Sirente-Velino Regional Park, as well as many other natural reserves and protected areas.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 2017, the ancient beech forests of the Abruzzo Lazio and Molise National Park of Europe were recognized as a World Heritage Site by UNESCO, a designation which gave the region its first prestigious site.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo is governed as a presidential style representative democracy with a multi-party system.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Executive power is exercised by the Regional Government.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Legislative power is vested in both the government and the regional council.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Regional Government (*Giunta regionale*) is presided over by the president of the region (*presidente della Regione*), who is elected for a five-year term.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The government is composed of the President and the eight ministers (*assessori*), including the Vice President (*Vicepresidente*) and an Undersecretary (*Sottosegretario*).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Minors make up 13.9% of the population, and seniors make up 26.5%.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] As of 2026, with a population density of 117.0 people per km2, the population density of Abruzzo is well below the national average of 195.1.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Among the provinces, the density varies: Pescara is the most densely populated with 253.2 inhabitants per km2, whereas L'Aquila is the least densely populated, with 56.8 inhabitants per km2, although it has the largest area.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The most serious demographic imbalance is between the mountainous areas of the interior and the coastal strip.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The largest province, L'Aquila, is situated entirely in the interior and has the lowest population density.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The movement of the population of Abruzzo from the mountains to the sea has led to the almost complete urbanization of the entire coastal strip, especially in the province of Teramo and Chieti.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The effects on the interior have been impoverishment and demographic aging, reflected by an activity rate in the province of L'Aquila which is the lowest among the provinces in Abruzzo – accompanied by geological degradation as a result of the absence of conservation measures.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the coastal strip, there is such a dense concentration of accommodations and activities that the environment has been negatively affected.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The policy of providing incentives for development has resulted in the setting-up of industrial zones, some of which (Vasto, Avezzano, Carsoli, Gissi, Val Vibrata, Val di Sangro) have made significant progress, while others (Val Pescara, L'Aquila) have run into trouble after their initial success.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The zones of Sulmona and Guardiagrele have turned out to be more or less failures.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Outside these zones, the main activities are agriculture and tourism.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Despite these environmental pressures, in 2016, the *Huffington Post* placed Abruzzo in fifth position among the 12 best regions in the world for quality of life.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] As of 2025, immigrants make up 11.6% of the population.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The 5 largest foreign countries of birth are Romania, Albania, Switzerland, Morocco, and Venezuela.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] After decades of emigration from the region, the main feature of the 1980s was immigration from developing countries.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The recent population increase was due to the positive net migration.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Until a few decades ago, Abruzzo was a backward region of Southern Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Since the 1950s, Abruzzo has shown steady economic growth.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 1951, the region's per capita income, or GDP, was only 53% of that of wealthier Northern Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The gap has since narrowed, being 65% in 1971 and 76% by 1994.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The region achieved the highest per capita GDP in Southern Italy, alongside the highest growth rate in the country.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The unemployment rate stood at 9.3% in 2020.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo is the 16th most productive region in the country, and is the 15th for GRP per capita among Italian regions.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] As of 2003, Abruzzo's per capita GDP was €19,506, or 84% of the national average of €23,181, compared to the average value for Southern Italy of €15,808.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 2006, the region's average GDP per capita was approximately 20,100 EUR.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The construction of motorways from Rome to Teramo (A24) and Rome to Pescara (A25), which provided better access to the region, is credited as a driver of public and private investments.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The 2009 L'Aquila earthquake led to a sharp economic slowdown.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] However, according to statistics at the end of 2010, some signals of recovery were noted.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Regional economic growth was recorded as 1.47%, which placed Abruzzo fourth among Italy's regions after Lazio, Lombardy, and Calabria.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 2011, Abruzzo's economic growth was +2.3%, making it the top-performing region in Southern Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] From the early 1950s to the mid-1990s, Abruzzo's industrial sector expanded rapidly, especially in mechanical engineering, transportation equipment, and telecommunications.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The structure of production in the region reflects the transformation of the economy from agriculture to industry and services.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The industrial sector relies on a few large enterprises and the predominance of small and medium ones.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the applied research field, there are major institutes and enterprises involved in the fields of pharmaceutics, biomedicine, electronics, aerospace, and nuclear physics.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The industrial infrastructure is dispersed throughout the region in industrial zones.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The most important of these are: Val Pescara, Val di Sangro, Val Trigno, Val Vibrata, and Conca del Fucino.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The province of Teramo is one of the most industrialized areas of Italy and of the region, with numerous small and medium-sized companies.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] It is followed by the province of Chieti and that of Pescara, which is also supported by tourism.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Val Vibrata (province of Teramo), on the border with the Marche region, is home to a myriad of small and medium-sized enterprises, especially in the textile and footwear sectors.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Val di Sangro (province of Chieti), on the other hand, is home to important multinationals and a factory belonging to the Fiat (Sevel) group.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The area of Valle Peligna (province of L'Aquila) is home to the famous Sulmona sugared almond confectionery industry.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Agriculture, based on small holdings, has modernised and produces high-quality products.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The mostly small-scale producers are active in wine, cereals, sugar beet, potatoes, olives, vegetables, fruit, and dairy products.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Traditional products are saffron and liquorice.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] By the late 20th and early 21st centuries, Montepulciano d'Abruzzo, the region's most famous wine, had become one of the most widely exported DOC-classed wines in Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] As for cereals, the durum wheat with over 1.5 million quintals constitutes the main cereal, followed by soft wheat (one million quintals), then barley (0.5 million quintals ); other crops are also grown, among them beetroot (2,500,000 quintals) and tobacco (45,000 quintals).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Tourism is an important economic sector; in the past decade, tourism has increased, mainly centered on its national parks and natural reserves, ski and beach resorts, in particular along the Trabocchi Coast.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo's castles and medieval towns, especially in the area of L'Aquila, have led to the creation of the nickname of "Abruzzoshire", along Tuscany's "Chiantishire".
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In spite of this, Abruzzo is still "off the beaten path" for most visitors to Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 2017, the ancient beech forests of the Abruzzo Lazio and Molise National Park were recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, with the region thus gaining its first prestigious site.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the inland mountain areas there are the ski resorts of Scanno, Ovindoli, Pescasseroli, Roccaraso, Campo Imperatore, Campo Felice, Rivisondoli, Pescocostanzo, and Pianoro Campitelli, where winter tourism is highly developed.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Visitors engage in sports such as alpine skiing, snowboarding, ski mountaineering, ski touring, cross-country skiing, and dog sledding.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Other trails and facilities are in Passolanciano-Majelletta, Campo Rotondo, Campo di Giove, Piani di Pezza, Voltigno, Centomonti, Macchiarvana, Monte Piselli.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Finally, tourism for historical and cultural purposes is also important, concentrated above all in the cities of Lanciano, Chieti, Teramo, Vasto, Giulianova, Sulmona, and in particular L'Aquila, which boasts many monuments, museums, castles, and churches, among which St.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Gabriel's shrine and Santa Maria di Collemaggio are of national importance.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Pescara, despite being a modern city, boasts monuments, churches, and museums of historical importance such as the Birthplace of Gabriele D'Annunzio Museum.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the inland mountain areas, there are ancient villages, castles, hermitages, sanctuaries, abbeys, and ancient churches.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo has many small and picturesque villages.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There are four main ports in Abruzzo: Pescara, Ortona, Vasto, and Giulianova.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Over the years, the Port of Pescara has become one of the most important tourist ports in Italy and on the Adriatic Sea.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Heavily damaged in World War II, it underwent major renovations for roughly sixty years.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] It now consists of a modern marina with advanced moorings and shipbuilding facilities.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] It has been awarded the European Union's Blue Flag for its services.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Port of Pescara has lost passenger traffic because of its shallowness and silting.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In Abruzzo, marine spatial planning tools such as SeaGIS have been developed to support the management of fisheries and aquaculture, reflecting ongoing planning efforts in the sector.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There is a significant disparity between the railways of the Abruzzo coast and the inland areas, which badly need modernization to improve the service, in particular the Rome-Pescara line.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Museo Archeologico Nazionale d'Abruzzo in Chieti houses the famed *Warrior of Capestrano statue,* which was found in a necropolis of the 6th century BC.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Every year on 28–29 August, L'Aquila's Santa Maria di Collemaggio commemorates the Perdonanza Celestiniana, the indulgence issued by Pope Celestine V to anyone who "truly repentant and confessed" would visit that Church from the Vespers of the vigil to the vespers of 29 August.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Sulmona's Holy Week is commemorated with traditional celebrations and rituals, such as "La Madonna che scappa in piazza", when a large statue of Mary, borne by a group of local fraternities, is carried across the square in procession.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Cocullo, in the province of L'Aquila, holds the annual "Festa dei serpari" (festival of snake handlers) in which a statue of St.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Dominic, covered with live snakes, is carried in a procession through the town; it attracts thousands of Italian and foreign visitors.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In many Abruzzo villages, Anthony the Great's feast is celebrated in January with massive, scenic bonfires.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In the past, the region of Abruzzo was well known for the transumanza, the seasonal movement of sheep flocks; these used to travel mostly southbound towards Puglia during the cold winter months.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Biagio, protector of wool dealers, is celebrated across the region.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] On 3 February in Taranta Peligna, every year since the sixteenth century, an evocative ritual is held: *panicelle*, or small loaves made of flour and water, in the shape of a blessing hand, are distributed among the faithful.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Historical figures from the region include: the Roman orator Asinius Pollio; Latin poets Sallust and Ovid, who were born in L'Aquila and Sulmona respectively; Gaius Cassius Longinus, Roman senator and leading instigator of the plot to kill Julius Caesar.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Pontius Pilate is said to have been native to the region.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Abruzzo's religious personalities include Saint Berardo; John of Capistrano; Thomas of Celano, author of three hagiographies of Saint Francis of Assisi; and Alessandro Valignano, who introduced Catholicism to the Far East and Japan.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Polish Pope John Paul II loved the mountains of Abruzzo, where he would retire often and pray in the church of San Pietro della Ienca.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Local personalities in the humanities include: writer Ignazio Silone, screenwriter Ennio Flaiano who co-wrote *La dolce vita*, philosopher Benedetto Croce, poet Gabriele D'Annunzio, composer Paolo Tosti, sculptor Venanzo Crocetti, and artist LorenzoArs.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Some international movies shot in Abruzzo include *The American*, Jean-Jacques Annaud's *The Name of the Rose*, Fellini's *La Strada* and *I Vitelloni*, Schwarzenegger's *Red Sonja*, *Ladyhawke*, *King David*, *Francesco*, *Keoma*, *The Barbarians*, *The Fox and the Child,* and *Krull*.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] is the most visited monument in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Before the 2009 earthquake, Abruzzo was the region with the highest number of castles and hill towns in Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] It still holds many of Italy's best-preserved medieval and Renaissance hill towns, twenty-three of which are among *I Borghi più belli d'Italia*.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] This listing recognises their scenic beauty, arts and culture, their historical importance, and quality of life.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The abrupt decline of Abruzzo's agricultural economy in the early to mid-20th century spared some of the region's historic hill towns from modern development.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Many lie entirely within regional and national parks.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Among the most best preserved are Castel del Monte and Santo Stefano di Sessanio, within the Gran Sasso National Park on the edge of the high plain of Campo Imperatore and nestled beneath the Apennines' highest peaks.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Both hill towns, which were ruled by the Medicis for over a century and a half, see relatively little tourism.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Between the two towns sits Rocca Calascio, the ruin of an ancient fortress popular with filmmakers.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Monteferrante and Roccascalegna are two of the most representative Abruzzo villages in the province of Chieti.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Within the Gran Sasso National Park also lies Castelli, an ancient pottery center whose artisans produced ceramics for most of the royal houses of Europe.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Civitella del Tronto played a crucial role in the history of the unification of Italy.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The fortress of Civitella is the most visited monument in the Abruzzo region today.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Other medieval hill towns located within Abruzzo's park system are Pacentro in the Maiella National Park and Pescasseroli in the Abruzzo National Park.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Pacentro, which features a 14th-century castle with two intact towers, has been little touched by modernisation.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Shrine of Gabriel of Our Lady of Sorrows, in the province of Teramo, which attracts some two million visitors per year, is one of the 15 most-visited sanctuaries in the world.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Giulianova is a notable example of a Renaissance "ideal city".
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The proximity to Rome, the protected areas, and scenic landscapes make the region one of the greenest in Europe.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The presence of quaint villages and its rich and varied culinary traditions are important tourist attractions.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 2015, the American organization Live and Invest Overseas included Abruzzo on its list of World's Top 21 Overseas Retirement Havens.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The study was based on such factors as climate, infrastructure, health care, safety, taxes, and cost of living.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] In 2017, the Chamber of Commerce of Pescara presented Abruzzo region to the annual conference of Live and Invest Overseas in the U.S. city of Orlando, Florida.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] One year later, in October 2018, Live and Invest Overseas held its first conference in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Harvard University bases an intensive summer Italian language and culture program in Vasto, a resort town on Abruzzo's southern coast.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Between the province of Teramo and L'Aquila, under the Gran Sasso Tunnel, is the Laboratori Nazionali del Gran Sasso (LNGS) of the INFN, one of the three underground astroparticle laboratories in Europe.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Istituto Zooprofilattico Sperimentale dell'Abruzzo e del Molise "Giuseppe Caporale", which conducts research in veterinary and environmental public health, is located in Teramo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The Gran Sasso Science Institute, located in L'Aquila, is an advanced research institute which offers doctorates in astroparticle physics, computer science, and mathematics, as well as urban studies and regional science, and which also conducts scientific research.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Interamnia World Cup, the largest international youth handball competition worldwide, takes place yearly in Teramo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] There are several football clubs in Abruzzo.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] Delfino Pescara 1936 is a Serie B club; based in Pescara, its home stadium is Stadio Adriatico – Giovanni Cornacchia.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The regional dialects of Abruzzo include *Teramano*, *Abruzzese Orientale Adriatico,* and *Abruzzese Occidentale*.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p01] The first two forms are dialects of the Southern Italian language also known as Neapolitan, since the region has been part of the Kingdom of Naples and the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies, while *Aquilano* is related to the Central Italian dialects including Romanesco.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Abruzzo's cuisine is renowned for its variety and richness.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Both the agricultural and coastal areas of Abruzzo have contributed to its cuisine.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Due to the mountains, much of Abruzzo was relatively isolated until the 20th century.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] This has contributed to preserving local culinary traditions.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Across the region, roast lamb is enjoyed in several variations.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Seafood is also popular, especially in coastal areas.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] The variety of fish available locally resulted in several fish-based *brodetti* ("broths"), coming from such places as Vasto, Giulianova, and Pescara.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] These broths are often made by cooking fish, flavored with tomatoes, herbs, and peperoncino, in an earthenware pot.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Other fish products are *scapece alla vastese*, baccalà all'abruzzese, and *coregone di Campotosto*, typical lake fish.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Also from Teramo are the spreadable sausages flavored with nutmeg, and liver sausages tasting of garlic and spices.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Atri and Rivisondoli are famous for cheeses.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Mozzarella, either fresh or seasoned, is made from ewe's milk, although a great number of lesser known varieties of these cheeses can be found all over Abruzzo and Molise.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Spreadable sausage flavored with nutmeg and liver sausage with garlic and spices are hallmarks of Teramo cuisine.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] *Ventricina* from the Vasto area is made with large pieces of fat and lean pork, pressed and seasoned with powdered sweet peppers and fennel, and encased in dried pig stomach.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] *Mortadella di Campotosto* (well known in Abruzzo) is an oval, dark-red *mortadella* with a white column of fat.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] They are generally sold in pairs, tied together.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Another name for the mortadella is *coglioni di mulo* (donkey's balls).
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] It is made from shoulder and loin meat, prosciutto trimmings, and fat.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] It is 80 percent lean meat; 25 percent is prosciutto (ham), and 20 percent is *pancetta*.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] The meat is minced and mixed with salt, pepper and white wine.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Atri and Rivisondoli are known for their cheeses.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Mozzarella (fresh or seasoned) is typically made from ewe's milk; many lesser-known cheeses are found throughout Abruzzo and Molise.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] The use of oil in regional mountain and sea dishes is important; among the most common oil products are the Aprutino Pescarese, the Pretuziano delle Colline Teramane, l'Olio extra vergine di oliva delle Valli Aquilane and Colline Teatine.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] The extra-virgin olive oil produced in Colline Teramane (Teramo hills) is marked by the DOP.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] The region has several cultivars that include Carboncella, Dritta (Dritta Francavillese and Dritta di Moscufo), Gentile del Chieti, Nostrana (Nostrana di Brisighella), and Sargano olive cultivars.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] Renowned wines such as Montepulciano DOCG, Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC and Controguerra DOC are judged to be amongst the world's finest.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo ranked No.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] In recent decades these wines have been joined, particularly, by wines from lesser known (heritage) white grapes, such as Pecorino, Cococciola, Passerina, Montonico bianco and Fiano.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] IGT wines are Alto Tirino, Colli Aprutini, Colli del Sangro, Colline Frentane, Colline Pescaresi, Colline Teatine, Del Vastese (or Histonium), Terre di Chieti, and Valle Peligna.
[src:sicily/abruzzo-p02] The region is also well known for the production of liqueurs such as Centerbe, Limoncello, Ratafia, and Genziana.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily's namesake is the Sicels, who inhabited the eastern part of the island during the Iron Age.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily has a rich and unique culture in arts, music, literature, cuisine, and architecture.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Its most prominent landmark is Mount Etna, the tallest active volcano in Europe, and one of the most active in the world, currently 3,403 m (11,165 ft) high.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The island has a typical Mediterranean climate.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] It is separated from Calabria by the Strait of Messina.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] It is one of the five Italian autonomous regions and is considered part of southern Italy.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The earliest archaeological record of human activity on the island dates to around 14,000 BC.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] By around 750 BC, Sicily had three Phoenician and around twelve Greek colonies along its coasts, becoming one of the centers of Magna Graecia.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Sicilian Wars of 580–265 BC were fought between the Carthaginians and Greeks, and the Punic Wars of 264–146 BC were fought between Rome and Carthage.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Roman province of Sicilia ended with the fall of the Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily was ruled during the Early Middle Ages by the Vandals, the Ostrogoths, the Byzantine Empire, and the Emirate of Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Norman conquest of southern Italy led to the creation of the County of Sicily in 1071, which was succeeded by the Kingdom of Sicily in 1130.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Following the Sicilian Vespers in 1282, Sicily was ruled by the Crown of Aragon and then the Monarchy of Spain, either in personal union with the crown or by a cadet branch, except for a brief period of Savoy and then Habsburg rule in 1713–1735.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 1816, the kingdom unified with the Kingdom of Naples to form the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Following the Expedition of the Thousand, an invasion led by Giuseppe Garibaldi, and a subsequent plebiscite, the island became part of the newly unified Italy in 1860.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily was given special status as an autonomous administrative division on 15 May 1946, 18 days before the 1946 Italian institutional referendum.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The name *Sicilia* was given to the Roman province in 241 BC.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] It is named after the Sicels, who inhabited the eastern part of the island during the Iron Age.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The ancient name of the island is *Trinacria* (Greek Τρινακρία "having three headlands") for its triangular shape, likely a re-interpretation of earlier (Homeric) *Thrinacia*.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Greek name was rendered as *Trīnācrĭa* in classical Latin (Virgil, Ovid).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Humans first colonized Sicily towards the end of the Late Pleistocene, around 16,000 years ago, by people associated with the Epigravettian culture.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Discoveries of dolmens on the island (dating to the second half of the third millennium BC) seem to offer new insights into the culture of primitive Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The impact of at least two influences is clear: the European one coming from the Northwest, and the Mediterranean influence of an eastern heritage.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The original classical-era inhabitants of Sicily comprised three defined groups of the ancient peoples of Italy: the Sicani, the Elymians and the Sicels.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The most prominent and by far the earliest of these were the Sicani, who (Thucydides writes) arrived from the Iberian Peninsula (perhaps Catalonia).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Some modern scholars, however, suggest classifying the Sicani as possibly an Illyrian tribe.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Important historical evidence has been discovered in the form of cave drawings by the Sicani, dated from the end of the Pleistocene epoch around 8000 BC.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Elymians, thought to have come from the area of the Aegean Sea, became the next tribe to join the Sicanians on Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] No evidence survives of warring between tribes, but the Sicanians moved eastwards when the Elymians settled in the northwest corner of the island.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Sicels are thought to have originated in Liguria; they arrived from mainland Italy in 1200 BC and forced the Sicanians to move back across Sicily and to settle in the middle of the island.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Other minor Italic groups who settled in Sicily included the Ausones (Aeolian Islands, Milazzo) and the Morgetes of Morgantina.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Phoenician settlements in the western part of the island predate the arrival of Greek colonists.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] From about 750 BC, the Greeks began to live in Sicily (Ancient Greek: Σικελία – *Sikelia*), establishing many significant settlements.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The most important colony was in Syracuse; others grew up at Akragas, Selinunte, Gela, Himera and Zancle.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The native Sicani and Sicel peoples became absorbed into the Hellenic culture with relative ease, and the area became part of Magna Graecia along with the coasts of the south of the Italian peninsula, which the Greeks had also colonised.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily had fertile soils, and the successful introduction of olives and grape vines fostered profitable trading.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Greek culture significantly centered around Greek religion, and the settlers built many temples throughout Sicily, including several in the *Valley of the Temples* at Agrigento.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Politics on the island became intertwined with those of Greece; Syracuse became desired by the Athenians who set out on the Sicilian Expedition (415–413 BC) during the Peloponnesian War.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Syracuse gained Sparta and Corinth as allies and, as a result, defeated the Athenian expedition.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The victors destroyed the Athenian army and their ships, selling most of the survivors into slavery.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Greek kingdom of Syracuse controlled most of eastern Sicily while Carthage controlled the western side.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The two cultures began to clash, leading to the Greek-Punic wars (between 580 and 265 BC).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Greek states had begun to make peace with the Roman Republic in 205 BC, before the Romans sought to annex Sicily as their republic's first province.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Rome attacked Carthage's holdings in Sicily in the First Punic War (264 to 241 BC) and won, making Sicily–with the exception of Syracuse–the first Roman province outside of the Italian Peninsula by 242 BC.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In the Second Punic War (218 to 201 BC), the Carthaginians attempted to recapture Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Some of the Greek cities on the island who were loyal to Rome switched sides to help the Carthaginians, prompting a Roman military response.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Archimedes, who lived in Syracuse, helped defend his city from Roman invasion; Roman troops killed him after they captured Syracuse in 212 BC.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Carthaginian attempt failed, and Rome became more unrelenting in its annihilation of the invaders; Roman consul M.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Valerian told the Roman Senate in 210 BC that "no Carthaginian remains in Sicily".
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] As the Roman Republic's granary, Sicily ranked as an important province, divided into two quaestorships: Syracuse to the east and Lilybaeum to the west.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Roman rule introduced the Latin language to the island, which underwent a slow process of latinisation but Sicilian culture remained largely Greek and the Greek language did not become extinct on the island, facilitating its re-hellenisation much later under the Byzantines.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The prosperity of the island went into sharp decline during the governorship of Verres (73 to 71 BC).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 70 BC, the noted statesman Cicero condemned the misgovernment of Verres in his oration *In Verrem*.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Various groups used the island as a power base at different times: slave insurgents occupied it during the First (135−132 BC) and Second (104−100 BC) Servile Wars.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sextus Pompey had his headquarters there during the Sicilian revolt of 44 to 36 BC.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Christianity first appeared in Sicily during the years following AD 200; between this time and AD 313, when Emperor Constantine the Great lifted the prohibition on Christianity, a significant number of Sicilians had become martyrs, including Agatha, Christina, Lucy, and Euplius.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily remained a Roman province for around 700 years.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Western Roman Empire began falling apart after the invasion of Vandals, Alans, and Sueves across the Rhine on the last day of 406.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Eventually the Vandals, after roaming about western and southern Hispania (present-day Iberia) for 20 years, moved to North Africa in 429 and occupied Carthage in 439.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Franks moved south from present-day Belgium.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Visigoths moved west and eventually settled in Aquitaine in 418; the Burgundians were settled in present-day Savoy in 443.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Vandals found themselves in a position to threaten Sicily – only 100 miles away from their North African bases.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] After taking Carthage, the Vandals, personally led by King Gaiseric, laid siege to Palermo in 440 as the opening act in an attempt to wrest the island from Roman rule.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Vandals made another attempt to take the island one year after the 455 sack of Rome, at Agrigento, but were defeated decisively by Ricimir in a naval victory off Corsica in 456.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The island remained under Roman rule until 469.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Vandals lost possession of the island 8 years later in 477 to the East Germanic tribe of the Ostrogoths, who then controlled Italy and Dalmatia.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The island was returned to the Ostrogoths by payment of tribute to their king Odoacer.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] He ruled Italy from 476 to 488 in the name of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Emperor.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Vandals kept a toehold in Lilybaeum, a port on the west coast.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] They lost this in 491 after making one last attempt to conquer the island from this port.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Ostrogothic conquest of Sicily (and of Italy as a whole) under Theodoric the Great began in 488.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Byzantine Emperor Zeno had appointed Theodoric as a military commander in Italy.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Goths were Germanic, but Theodoric fostered Roman culture and government and allowed freedom of religion.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 461 from the age of seven or eight until 17 or 18 Theodoric had become a Byzantine hostage; he resided in the great palace of Constantinople, was favoured by Emperor Leo I (r.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] 457–474) and learned to read, write and do arithmetic.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] After taking areas occupied by the Vandals in North Africa, Justinian I retook Italy as an ambitious attempt to recover the lost provinces in the West.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The re-conquests marked an end to over 150 years of accommodating policies with tribal invaders.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] His first target was Sicily, leading to the Gothic War (535–554) between the Ostrogoths and the Eastern Roman Empire, also known as the Byzantine Empire.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Justinian's general Belisarius was assigned to the military task.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily was used as a base for the Byzantines to conquer the rest of Italy, including Naples, Rome, and Milan.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] It took five years before the Ostrogoth capital Ravenna fell in 540.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] However, the new Ostrogoth king Totila counterattacked, moving down the Italian peninsula, plundering and conquering Sicily in 550.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Totila was defeated and killed in the Battle of Taginae by Byzantine general Narses in 552 but Italy was in ruins.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] At the time of the reconquest Greek was still the predominant language spoken on the island.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily was invaded by the Arab forces of Caliph Uthman in 652, but the Arabs failed to make permanent gains.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] They returned to Syria with their booty.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Raids seeking loot continued until the mid-8th century.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Eastern Roman Emperor Constans II moved from Constantinople to Syracuse in 660.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The following year he launched an assault from Sicily against the Lombard Duchy of Benevento, which occupied most of southern Italy.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Rumors that the capital of the empire was to be moved to Syracuse probably cost Constans his life, as he was assassinated in 668.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] A brief usurpation in Sicily by Mezezius was quickly suppressed by this emperor.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Contemporary accounts report that the Greek language was widely spoken on the island during this period.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 740 Emperor Leo III the Isaurian transferred Sicily from the jurisdiction of the church of Rome to that of Constantinople, placing the island within the eastern branch of the Church.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 826 Euphemius, the Byzantine commander in Sicily, having apparently killed his wife, forced a nun to marry him.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Emperor Michael II caught wind of the matter and ordered general Constantine to end the marriage and cut off Euphemius' head.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Euphemius rose up, killed Constantine, and then occupied Syracuse; he, in turn, was defeated and driven out to North Africa.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] He offered the rule of Sicily to Ziyadat Allah, the Aghlabid Emir of Tunisia, in return for a position as a general and a place of safety.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] A Muslim army was then sent to the island consisting of Arabs, Berbers, Cretans, and Persians.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Muslim conquest of Sicily was a see-saw affair and met with fierce resistance.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] It took over a century for Byzantine Sicily to be conquered; the largest city, Syracuse, held out until 878 and the Greek city of Taormina fell in 902.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] It was not until 965 that all of Sicily was conquered by the Arabs.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In the 11th-century Byzantine armies carried out a partial reconquest of the island under George Maniakes, but it was their Norman mercenaries who would eventually complete the island's reconquest at the end of the century.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The language spoken in Sicily under Arab rule was Siculo-Arabic and Arabic influence is present in some Sicilian words today.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Although long extinct in Sicily, the language has developed into what is now the Maltese language on the islands of Malta today.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] A description of Palermo was given by Ibn Hawqal, an Arab merchant who visited Sicily in 950.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] A walled suburb, called the Al-Kasr (the palace), is the centre of Palermo to this day, with the great Friday mosque on the site of the later Roman cathedral.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The suburb of al-Khalisa (modern Kalsa) contained the Sultan's palace, baths, a mosque, government offices, and a private prison.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Ibn Hawqal estimated there were 7,000 butchers trading in 150 shops.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Muslim rule introduced lemons, oranges, pistachios, and sugar cane, as well as cotton and mulberries for sericulture, and introduced the Qanat to improve irrigation systems for agriculture.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Around 1050, the western half of Sicily was ethnically and culturally distinct from central and eastern Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] During this time, there was also a small Jewish presence in Sicily, evidence seen in the catacombs discovered on the island.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Palermo was initially ruled by the Aghlabids; later it was the centre of the Emirate of Sicily, which was under the nominal suzerainty of the Fatimid Caliphate.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Muslim sovereignty was never absolute across the island, and the creation of three subdivisions served to distinguish different approaches to government.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Under the Arab rule the island was divided in three administrative regions, or "vals", roughly corresponding to the three "points" of Sicily: Val di Mazara in the west; Val Demone in the northeast; and Val di Noto in the southeast.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Parts of the island were re-occupied before revolts were quashed.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] By the 11th century, the Emirate of Sicily began to fragment as intra-dynastic quarrelling fractured the Muslim government.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 1038, seventy years after losing their last cities in Sicily, the Byzantines under the Greek general George Maniakes invaded the island together with their Varangian and Norman mercenaries.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Maniakes was killed in a Byzantine civil war in 1043 before completing a reconquest and the Byzantines withdrew.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Later the Normans invaded in 1061 and after taking Apulia and Calabria, Roger I occupied Messina with an army of 700 knights.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 1068, Roger I was victorious at Misilmeri.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Most crucial was the siege of Palermo, whose fall in 1071 eventually resulted in all Sicily coming under Norman control.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The conquest was completed in 1091 when they captured Noto the last Arab stronghold.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Palermo continued to be the capital under the Normans.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Normans formed a small but violent ruling class.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] They destroyed many of the Arab towns in Sicily, and very few physical remains survive from the Arab era.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Norman Hauteville family appreciated and admired the rich and layered culture in which they now found themselves.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] They also introduced into Sicily their own culture, customs, and politics from Normandy.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Many Normans in Sicily adopted the habits and comportment of Muslim rulers and their Byzantine subjects in dress, language, literature, even to the extent of having palace eunuchs and, according to some accounts, a harem.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] While Roger I died in 1101, his wife Adelaide ruled until 1112 when their son Roger II of Sicily came of age.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Having succeeded his brother Simon as Count of Sicily, Roger II was ultimately able to raise the status of the island to a kingdom in 1130, along with his other holdings, which included the Maltese Islands and the Duchies of Apulia and Calabria.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Roger II appointed the powerful Greek George of Antioch to be his "emir of emirs" and continued the syncretism of his father.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] During this period, the Kingdom of Sicily was prosperous and politically powerful, becoming one of the wealthiest states in all of Europe—even wealthier than the Kingdom of England.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The court of Roger II became the most luminous centre of culture in the Mediterranean, both from Europe and the Middle East, like the multi-ethnic Caliphate of Córdoba, then only just eclipsed.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] This attracted scholars, scientists, poets, artists, and artisans of all kinds.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Laws were issued in the language of the community to whom they were addressed in Norman Sicily, at the time when the culture was still heavily Arab and Greek.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Governance was by rule of law which promoted justice.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Muslims, Jews, Byzantine Greeks, Lombards, and Normans worked together fairly amicably.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] During this time many extraordinary buildings were constructed.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] However this situation changed as the Normans imported immigrants from Normandy, England, Lombardy, Piedmont, Provence and Campania to secure the island.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Linguistically, the island shifted from being one-third Greek- and two-thirds Arabic-speaking at the time of the Norman conquest to becoming fully Latinised.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In terms of religion the island became completely Roman Catholic (bearing in mind that until 1054 the Churches owing allegiance to the Pope and the Patriarch of Constantinople belonged to one Church); Sicily before the Norman conquest was under the Eastern Orthodox Patriarch.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] After a century, the Norman Hauteville dynasty died out; the last direct descendant and heir of Roger II, Constance, married Emperor Henry VI.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] This eventually led to the crown of Sicily being passed to the Hohenstaufen dynasty, who were Germans from Swabia.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The last of the Hohenstaufens, Frederick II, the only son of Constance, was one of the greatest and most cultured men of the Middle Ages.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] His mother's will had asked Pope Innocent III to undertake the guardianship of her son.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Frederick was four when at Palermo, he was crowned King of Sicily in 1198.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Frederick received no systematic education and was allowed to run free in the streets of Palermo.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] There he picked up the many languages he heard spoken, such as Arabic and Greek, and learned some of the lore of the Jewish community.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] At age twelve, he dismissed Innocent's deputy regent and took over the government; at fifteen he married Constance of Aragon, and began his reclamation of the imperial crown.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Subsequently, due to Muslim rebellions, Frederick II destroyed the remaining Muslim presence in Sicily, estimated at 60,000 people, moving all to the city of Lucera in Apulia between 1221 and 1226.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Conflict between the Hohenstaufen house and the Papacy led, in 1266, to Pope Innocent IV crowning the French prince Charles, count of Anjou and Provence, as the king of both Sicily and Naples.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Strong opposition to French officialdom due to mistreatment and taxation saw the local peoples of Sicily rise up, leading in 1282 to an insurrection known as the War of the Sicilian Vespers, which eventually saw almost the entire French population on the island killed.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] During the war, the Sicilians turned to Peter III of Aragon, son-in-law of the last Hohenstaufen king, for support after being rejected by the Pope.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Peter gained control of Sicily from the French, who, however, retained control of the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] A crusade was launched in August 1283 against Peter III and the Crown of Aragon by Pope Martin IV (a pope from Île-de-France), but it failed.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The wars continued until the peace of Caltabellotta in 1302, which saw Peter's son Frederick III recognized as the king of the Isle of Sicily, while Charles II was recognized as the king of Naples by Pope Boniface VIII.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily was ruled as an independent kingdom by relatives of the kings of Aragon until 1409 and then as part of the Crown of Aragon.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In October 1347, in Messina, Sicily, the Black Death first arrived in Europe.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Between the 15th and 18th centuries, waves of Greeks from the Peloponnese (such as the Maniots) and Arvanites migrated to Sicily in large numbers to escape persecution after the Ottoman conquest of the Peloponnese.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] They brought with them Eastern Orthodoxy as well as the Greek and Arvanitika languages, once again adding onto the extensive Byzantine/Greek influence.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The onset of the Spanish Inquisition in 1492 led to Ferdinand II decreeing the expulsion of all Jews from Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The eastern part of the island was hit by destructive earthquakes in 1542 and 1693.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Just a few years before the latter earthquake, the island was struck by a plague.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The earthquake in 1693 took an estimated 60,000 lives.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] There were revolts during the 17th century, but these were quelled with force, especially the revolts of Palermo and Messina.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] North African slave raids discouraged settlement along the coast until the 19th century.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Treaty of Utrecht in 1713 saw Sicily assigned to the House of Savoy; however, this period of rule lasted only seven years, as it was exchanged for the island of Sardinia with Emperor Charles VI of the Austrian Habsburg Dynasty.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] While the Austrians were concerned with the War of the Polish Succession, a Bourbon prince, Charles from Spain was able to conquer Sicily and Naples.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] At first Sicily was able to remain as an independent kingdom under personal union, while the Bourbons ruled over both from Naples.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] However, the advent of Napoleon's First French Empire saw Naples taken at the Battle of Campo Tenese and Bonapartist King of Naples was installed.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Ferdinand III, the Bourbon, was forced to retreat to Sicily which he was still in control of with the help of British naval protection.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Following this, Sicily joined the Napoleonic Wars, and subsequently the British under Lord William Bentinck established a military and diplomatic presence on the island to protect against a French invasion.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicilian volunteers joined the British military to form the Royal Sicilian Regiment, which saw action at the Battle of Maida and then transferred to Iberia.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] After the wars were won, Sicily and Naples formally merged as the Two Sicilies under the Bourbons.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Major revolutionary movements occurred in 1820 and 1848 against the Bourbon government with Sicily seeking independence; the second of which, the 1848 revolution resulted in a short period of independence for Sicily.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] However, in 1849 the Bourbons retook control of the island and dominated it until 1860.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Expedition of the Thousand led by Giuseppe Garibaldi captured Sicily in 1860, as part of the *Risorgimento*.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The conquest started at Marsala, and native Sicilians joined him in the capture of the southern Italian peninsula.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Garibaldi's march was completed with the siege of Gaeta, where the final Bourbons were expelled and Garibaldi announced his dictatorship in the name of Victor Emmanuel II of Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily became part of the Kingdom of Sardinia after a referendum in which more than 75% of Sicily voted in favour of the annexation on 21 October 1860 (although not everyone was allowed to vote).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] As a result of the proclamation of the Kingdom of Italy, Sicily became part of the kingdom on 17 March 1861.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Sicilian economy (and the wider *mezzogiorno* economy) remained relatively underdeveloped after the Italian unification, in spite of the strong investments made by the Kingdom of Italy in terms of modern infrastructure, and this caused an unprecedented wave of emigration.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In 1894, organisations of workers and peasants known as the *Fasci Siciliani* protested against the bad social and economic conditions of the island, but they were suppressed in a few days.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] This period was also characterized by the first contact between the Sicilian Mafia (the crime syndicate also known as Cosa Nostra) and the Italian government.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Mafia's origins are still uncertain, but it is generally accepted that it emerged in the 18th century initially in the role of private enforcers hired to protect the property of landowners and merchants from the groups of *briganti* who frequently pillaged the countryside and towns.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The battle against the Mafia made by the Kingdom of Italy was controversial and ambiguous.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Carabinieri (the military police of Italy) and sometimes the Royal Italian Army were often involved in fights against the mafia members, but their efforts were frequently useless because of the weakness of the Italian judicial system and cooperation between the mafia and local governments.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Messina earthquake of 28 December 1908 killed more than 80,000 people.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In the 1920s, the fascist regime began taking stronger military action, led by Cesare Mori (nicknamed the "Iron Prefect" for his iron-fisted campaigns), against the Sicilian Mafia, the first that ended with considerable success.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] An Allied invasion of Sicily during World War II began on 10 July 1943.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In preparation for the invasion, the Allies revitalised the Mafia to aid them.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The invasion of Sicily contributed to the 25 July crisis; in general, the Allied victors were warmly embraced by Sicilians.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In the aftermath of World War II, Italy became a republic in 1946.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Under the Constitution of Italy, Sicily is one of five regions with autonomy.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Both the partial Italian land reform and special funding from the Italian government's *Cassa per il Mezzogiorno* (*Fund for the South*) from 1950 to 1984 helped the Sicilian economy.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] During this period, the economic and social condition of the island was generally improved because of investments in infrastructure (such as motorways and airports) and the creation of industrial and commercial areas.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In the 1980s, the Mafia was weakened by another campaign led by magistrates Giovanni Falcone and Paolo Borsellino.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Between 1990 and 2005, the unemployment rate fell from about 23% to 11%.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The Cosa Nostra has traditionally been the most powerful group in Sicily, especially around Palermo.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] A police investigation in the summer of 2019 confirmed strong links between the Palermo area Sicilian Mafia and American organized crime, particularly the Gambino crime family.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] According to *La Repubblica*, "Off they go, through the streets of Passo di Rigano, Boccadifalco, Torretta and at the same time, Brooklyn, Staten Island, [and] New Jersey.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily has a roughly triangular shape, earning it the name *Trinacria*.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] To the north-east, it is separated from Calabria and the rest of the Italian mainland by the Strait of Messina, about 3 km (1.9 mi) wide in the north, and about 16 km (9.9 mi) wide in the southern part.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The northern and southern coasts are each about 280 km (170 mi) long measured as a straight line, while the eastern coast measures around 180 km (110 mi); total coast length is estimated at 1,484 km (922 mi).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The total area of the island is 25,711 km2 (9,927 sq mi), while the Autonomous Region of Sicily (which includes the smaller surrounding islands of Lipari, Egadi, Ustica, and Pantelleria) has an area of 27,708 km2 (10,698 sq mi).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The terrain of inland Sicily is mostly hilly and is intensively cultivated wherever possible.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Along the northern coast, the mountain ranges of Madonie, 2,000 m (6,600 ft), Nebrodi, 1,800 m (5,900 ft), and Peloritani, 1,300 m (4,300 ft), are an extension of the mainland Apennines.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The cone of Mount Etna dominates the eastern coast.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] In the southeast lie the lower Hyblaean Mountains, 1,000 m (3,300 ft).
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] The mines of the Enna and Caltanissetta districts were part of a leading sulphur-producing area throughout the 19th century, but have declined since the 1950s.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] Sicily and its surrounding small islands have some highly active volcanoes.
[src:sicily/sicily-p01] This is due to Sicily being geographically on the northern edge of the African Plate.
